1. Hide permission
2. Use type from spec
3. Spec could be update
4. Metadata in update form should be empty rather than {}
5. Add help text

commit_message:
Improve profile update form

1. Hide permission
2. Use type from spec
3. Spec could be update
4. Metadata in update form should be empty rather than {}
5. Add help text

Change-Id: I9f22d54b9a1784346929d68e63d9dcaabbdd2a14

commit_message:
Improving GlanceStoreException

This code improves current implementation of base
store exception with several things:
1. default message shouldn't be an empty string
and has to provide some information.
2. __init__ has to accept position parameter with
message string to bring glance_store to conformity
with glance.
3. 'super' should use GlanceStoreException instead of
just Exception.

Note: This matches the behaviour of glance_store's exceptions
with glance's.

Co-authored-by: Mike Fedosin <mfedosin@mirantis.com>
Co-authored-by: Stuart McLaren <stuart.​mclaren@hp.​com>

Closes-bug: 1501443

Change-Id: I04d25874de1c0ec0c46d094c4d9144412e0ae5c9
(cherry picked from commit 845254f5e17d159964249bc8d8cb2c84bf110e92)

commit_message:
Avoid oslo.messaging 2.6.0 and 2.6.1

When using those the tests (both unit and functional) will block,
eventually timing out. With this change we should be able to unwedge
aodh's CI.

Change-Id: Idbf05e5f9424a0f7360e220936b98b2984ca2b04

commit_message:
Removed $$defaultConfiguration, renamed 'api' to 'apiRoot'

The $$defaultConfiguration injector serves no real purpose
that wouldn't be met by manipulating the available list of
objects in the $$configuration response itself. Also, 'api'
is not a particularly descriptive property name, so I
changed it to 'apiRoot'.

Change-Id: I5f459d73ae2f7902a33e8125d94ad89b6ee17ab2

(2 comments)

At a minimum, install_required_sw() doesn't work on Solaris. (The warning it produces complains about "this Linux distribution," even.)

The other thing that jumps out at me to check on Solaris is the long options; the script has some fallback logic but I'm not sure how well that's been tested, and if getopt doesn't support long options then you lose the ability to specify database details. (That should be fixed by providing short options for the database config.)

I don't see anything else obvious, but it's been years since I've had to deal with Solaris. Obviously ideally we'd want Solaris CI resources to make sure that this script continues to work (and all of its features do, too).'}, {'account_id': 6835, 'date': '2015-07-08 02:04:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Log request headers in debug mode

Log all request headers in API server for user debugging. For X-*
headers, only show the murano own headers and several useful
headers added by keystone auth middleware, and skip other X-*
headers to make log more clear.

Change-Id: I5a73e4684e5dd9ca826b097a830505d5566c4395
Closes-Bug: #1505202

commit_message:
Validate src_ip_adress, dest_ip_address and ip_version

The FwaaS API should not allow the creation of firewall rules where
the ip_version is set to 4, but the source or destination IPs are IPv6
addresses

APIImpact
DocImpact

Closes-Bug: #1487599

Change-Id: Iad680996a47adcf27f9dc7e0bc0fea924fff4f9f

so looking at the pool api test that failed, i can't see why it failed.  Looking through the neutron logs I know that the LB does go ACTIVE, but only after all the tests fail.  The test that ran before the test that failed appears to run the _delete_pool method [1], but after that the logs don't show any GET requests checking the LB status, it just goes straight to creating a listener, which is the first request the first test that fails does.  \

I know the _delete_pool method does wait but it seems like in this case something is causing it to continue.  Perhaps there is a hole in the wait_for_status loop logic?

commit_message:
[LBaaS v2] Improve API tests performance

API tests shouldn't require booting real nova instances and can be
limited by creating DB entities. That is why it is beter to use
noop drivers for Octavia in API tests as it allows to significantly
accelerate test runs.

Changing interval_time in _wait_for_load_balancer_status method
from 10 sec to 1 sec allows to decrease test execution time while
keeping the average number of retries low (0 or 1).
Removed excessive _wait_for_load_balancer_status calls in tests.

Fixed operations order in
test_update_load_balancer_missing_admin_state_up,
test_update_load_balancer_missing_description and
test_update_load_balancer_missing_name.

Fixed gate_hook to take into account recent changes to the
apiv2 job structure.

Depends-On: Ia26bd8cb28dccbb021b2a2f64a9b7e6ef498ff4c
Change-Id: I4a5ea91ed63ddcc1c560cde94bd7d461aca3c49e
Closes-Bug: #1498532
Closes-Bug: #1497471

commit_message:
api tests: don't hide exception when creating load balancer

When the test fails, it's not clear what happened. We should not hide
details about it from those who will review test failure logs.

Change-Id: If68b4f93820085c4d9154d6b2aae8529f9c69da8
Related-Bug: #1505932

commit_message:
Fix error returned when an HA router is updated to DVR

Before this patch, the code compares the 'ha' flag that
comes in from the user, and the current state of the 'distributed'
flag in the DB. This is wrong because if a router is currently
HA in the DB, and the update request contains only
{'distributed': True}, then the 'ha' flag from the request
is None and the error condition is never raised!

The reason the unit tests
(Specifically test_migrate_ha_router_to_distributed)
did not catch this issue is because
of another bug: The _update_router helper method in the L3 HA
unit tests had an 'ha' default value of True, when it should
have had a default value of None. Setting it to None fails
the unit test (Because it raises the wrong exception),
and the contents of the patch makes the unit test pass.

Change-Id: Ie979b6a8400490b578ded17dc6529529e9637b34
Closes-Bug: #1505375

commit_message:
QoS SR-IOV: allow to reset vf rate when VF is assigend to VM

delete_bandwidth_limit method is called in 2 scenarios:
1. when deleting a port
2. when removing a policy from a port

self.eswitch_mgr.clear_max_rate is valdating if VF is not assigned to VM
which is good for case 1, but prevent reseting the max rate for case 2.
for case 2 the delete_bandwidth_limit should  call _set_vf_max_rate with max_kbps=0
to reset VF max rate for assigned VM.

Closes-Bug: #1504165

Change-Id: Ief708531708b8faa918603298d49d39ef5ba2df5

commit_message:
Fix rule generation for single and all host rules

iptables outputs single-host rules with a prefix on the
end (/32 or /128) and completely omits /0 rules since they
allow everything.

This patch fixes our rule generation to match that pattern
so iptables counters don't get destroyed on these rules on
every reload.

Closes-Bug: #1502917
Change-Id: Ifbdfbafd6cf37c6ef7385cd5f1d2df65cc19797a

commit_message:
Correct MAC representation to match iptables output

We were previously using the netaddr's mac_unix format
(which leaves off leading 0's) to generate iptables rules
based on MAC addresses. While iptables accepts this format,
it's not returned this way in the output so the iptables
rule matching code would never find the match for these
rules, causing the loss of counters on these rules on every
reload.

This patch corrects this with a custom dialect that matches
the iptables format.

Closes-Bug: #1502901
Change-Id: Ia45ebde8c4684e12030469323e18367a54d1518b

commit_message:
Fix inconsistency in DHCPv6 hosts and options generation

The DHCP agent is inconsistent in how it handles subnets whose
ipv6_address_mode is not slaac.  While the DHCP agent writes out both
DHCPv6 host entries and DHCPv6 options for ports scoped by the subnet
for dnsmasq to use, subnet specific options are not written.

This patch addresses this inconsistency by generating subnet specific
options when the subnet's ipv6_address_mode is not slaac.

Closes-Bug: #1501451

Change-Id: I372c93fa5667e955c7b81181daa2e66f47d85fdf

commit_message:
Fix kwarg assignment in objects.py

This change modifies the kwargs in the object instantiation to
use immutable default assignments. This is for object safety,
since a mutable object will not point to a new memory address
on modification. In Python, lists and dicts should not be used
as default assignments for kwargs.

Change-Id: I73993df12ca317161ba32e02a98a5f40ef8904f3

This patch adds support for Linux Bridges to os-net-config. This is
done completely with ifcfg files, brctl is not used. Hierarchy is
preserved, so a Linux Bridge may have a Linux Bond as a member,
which in turn may have multiple interfaces as members.

This change depends on the change to add support for Linux Bonds.

commit_message:
Add Linux Bridge capability to os-net-config ifcfg

This patch adds support for Linux Bridges to os-net-config. This is
done completely with ifcfg files, brctl is not used directly.
Hierarchy is preserved, so a Linux Bridge may have a Linux Bond
as a member, which in turn may have multiple interfaces as members.
This changeset has been updated to include a more specific example
for Linux bridge configuration (that doesn't combine bridging and
bonding).

This change depends on the change to add support for Linux Bonds.

Change-Id: I1ddacd514b02af30139a868071d82cde19b1f946

commit_message:
Never run Flask application with debug mode

Flask server in debug mode allows users to execute any Python code
on a server, which is a security issue for us.

Change-Id: I9e12510b0abb04182e85bf3f73cdad29e1f8d382
Closes-Bug: #1506419

commit_message:
Fix purging of raw_template rows

Templates referenced in the prev_raw_template_id column of the stack
table are not filtered by the purge_deleted script and end up being
removed. This fixes it by making sure that we consider them when
filtering.

Change-Id: I8bab657dfe77b7cef5971e370f6b4f9825a22ba8

[{'created': '2015-10-05 14:50:26.000000000', 'message': 'DVR: notify specific agent when creating floating ip

Currently when floating ip is created a lot of useless action
is happening: floating ip router is scheduled, all l3 agents where
router is scheduled are notified about router update, all agents
request full router info from server. All this becomes a big
performance problem at scale with lots of compute nodes.

In fact on (assocciated) Floating IP creation we really need
to notify specific l3 agent on compute node where associated
VM port is located and do not need to schedule router and
bother other agents where rourter is scheduled. This should
significally decrease unneeded load on neutron server at scale.

There is already a patch for floatng ip update,
I will also submit a patch for floating ip delete as well.

commit_message:
DVR: notify specific agent when creating floating ip

Currently when floating ip is created, a lot of useless action
is happening: floating ip router is scheduled, all l3 agents where
router is scheduled are notified about router update, all agents
request full router info from server. All this becomes a big
performance problem at scale with lots of compute nodes.

In fact on (associated) Floating IP creation we really need
to notify specific l3 agent on compute node where associated
VM port is located and do not need to schedule router and
bother other agents where rourter is scheduled. This should
significally decrease unneeded load on neutron server at scale.

Partial-Bug: #1486828
Change-Id: I0cbe8c51c3714e6cbdc48ca37135b783f8014905

commit_message:
Ditch Subs

Initially, Subs was introduced to substitute sensitive data from logs
which are getting included into diagnostic snapshot.
However, it was turned off by default since fuel 5.1

And we're in a situation where this piece of code was left untouched
for almost 2 year or so.

By getting rid of it, we is going to solve few issues:
1) devs will no longer need to spend time to maintain unused piece of
code.
2) shotgun will stop to modify the actual data inside of log
files. Therefore, this will allow us to significally reduce waste of
disk space and i/o on preparing copy of locally included logs.

Change-Id: Id78e369ea04e2847025c15150038de5f508a33af
Related-Bug: #1445311

commit_message:
Fix iptables comments for bare jump rules

This fixes the order of arguments in iptables rules that
are bare jumps (e.g. '-j other-chain').

The previous code was only catching jump rules that appeared
after a chain definition.

Closes-Bug: #1502932
Change-Id: I490792eb08c67a32f9b286d933a776fb76840b6b

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-30 12:12:17.000000000', 'message': 'Enable radosgw support in ironic

Ceph has a swift compatible API called radosgw. Although it is
compatible, there are some differences with swift in how temp URLs
are generated. This change adds a new config option called
temp_url_endpoint_type, which allows generation of temp URL depending
on the underlying object storage API.

Implements: blueprint radosgw-temp-url

Change-Id: I79cfe92aa19a2a0520fee2455f094d728c748d5c
'}, {'created': '2015-10-01 08:13:12.000000000', 'message': 'Enable radosgw support in ironic

Ceph has a swift compatible API called radosgw. Although it is
compatible, there are some differences with swift in how temp URLs
are generated. This change adds a new config option called
temp_url_endpoint_type, which allows generation of temp URL depending
on the underlying object storage API.

commit_message:
Enable radosgw support in ironic

Ceph has a swift compatible API called radosgw. Although it is
compatible, there are some differences with swift in how temp URLs
are generated. This change adds a new config option called
temp_url_endpoint_type, which allows generation of temp URL depending
on the underlying object storage API.

Implements: blueprint radosgw-temp-url

Change-Id: I79cfe92aa19a2a0520fee2455f094d728c748d5c

commit_message:
switch to oslo.cache

Use oslo.cache now that it's been made available.

Note that we only deprecate the cache backends, but not remove
them, they are public APIs and subject to deprecation.

Also remove most of the caching code, but keep the portions
that register backends, since they are still available.

Note that the tests that were deleted were testing cache
functionality, they now exist in oslo.cache.

Co-Authored-By: Brant Knudson <bknudson@us.ibm.com>

Change-Id: I39d3ff1dd2edad79effa56450b444174b09f971e

Use context manager in backup tests for limit restore execution

commit_message:
Interpolate the explanation string not whole HTML body

The only reason this exists is that I promised to do it.
But in our case, there's no big advantage, and here's why.

The general thinking goes that strings must be interpolated
first because the body may contain a syntax that confuses the
interpolation. So this patch makes the code "more correct".
However, our HTML template is tightly controlled. It's not
like it contains additional percents.

So I'll just leave this here for now while I'm asking if
the content type is set correctly.

Change-Id: Ia18aeb0f94ef389f8b95450986a566e5fa06aa10

commit_message:
Do collector setup and storage cleanup for all backends

It appears that a bit of overzealous copy and pasting of commands has
meant that:

* the number of collectors was not being set for mongodb, which may
  be a cause of performance issues in the gate
* the cleanup was not being called for the sql backend, which leaves
  behind wsgi config files when that backend is chosen

Change-Id: I013f14f8b167e564f794333c0fe5c8f421bb25a9

commit_message:
Add horizon setting for cinder backup

This change makes the cinder backup enable flag in the Horizon
configuration a variable.

It also enables this flag automatically through group_vars when
cinder_service_backup_program_enabled = True.

Change-Id: Ib64532bbd7a3774f16766de0d3d221579aecc9ff
Closes-Bug: #1504279

commit_message:
Create bareon project

This project is to provide a flexible and easy to
use operating system installation tool. It is to focus
on providing advanced partitioning functionality as well
as advanced pre-configuration features. It differs from
existent great cloud oriented solutions like Ironic Python
Agent (OS provisioning) and Cloud init (OS pre-configuration).
It is to be a tool similar to old plain OS installation tools like
anaconda or debian-installer but dramatically more convenient.

Corresponding project creation change: Ia6c59aefb260712d34d73a49f186e072637d7de5
Change-Id: Ieb1e6dcc13c28e4d17bedb4c2b55fd65b79fc48f

commit_message:
Capture timing information for failed atomic actions

If an atomic action throws an exception, it will still capture timing
information; the choice of whether or not to display that information
can be left to reports. Also adds unit tests to ensure this behavior.

Change-Id: I12e96b8ac6c40904f46022a6633714d5c9b1dea1

(17 comments)

Overall looks great. There's a bunch of comments here but it's mostly correcting a copy/paste of Compute.

One thing I'm a little unsure of is the inclusion of the example code using line numbers. I wonder if it might just be easier to have a separate file per example, and then tell the literalinclude to only show the function we care about. The pyobject option at http://sphinx-doc.org/markup/code.html#directive-literalinclude shows how that might work. If we can do that, then each file is runnable on its own and remains testable, and is also less fragile as changes wouldn't cause one or more line number positions to have to change."}, {'account_id': 1112, 'date': '2015-10-02 01:28:59.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 1112, 'date': '2015-10-02 01:29:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

(17 comments)

I know what you mean about using the line numbers. Terry had similar misgivings about it [1]. I'm still a bit unsure too. I still think that if we went with the one file per example route we would wind up with an astounding number of example files.

However, I did try out your suggestion with the literalinclude+pyobject and it works amazingly well. We only have to reference the function name and Sphinx brings the whole function in. Seems like exactly what we need. We can keep functionally similar methods together in a single module but not have to worry about futzing around with line numbers.

Let me know what you think. I'm on vacation for the next few days but will be back on Oct. 7.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/215823/2/doc/source/users/guides/compute.rst"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-02 02:05:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

commit_message:
Docs overhaul

* Docs are now ordered by STIG ID number to make them easier to browse.
* Deployer notes are better organized.
* Script + CSV added for automated documentation generation.

Implements: blueprint security-hardening

Change-Id: Ib87bec701eddf1601574f4e027f301c775e5e1cd

@Dan: for hieradata overrides/additions, I'd prefer not to use parameter_defaults, as we already have parameters wired in to pass in additional hieradata, so we'd be duplicating that interface.

If something is deemed important enough to wire in via a new parameter in the role template (vs some third-party extraconfig not enabled by default), then it should be wired in to the top-level template IMO, as this makes it much easier for folks building UI's on the templates to ask for appropriate input."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-09-25 14:52:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Ref my comment, personally I would prefer it if we don't start using parameter_defaults to wire in values to the "core" role templates.

IMO we do need to work out and document guidelines around this, but if it's important enough to add a new parameter, it should be wired in to overcloud-without-mergepy, and if it's a niche option which isn't appropriate to the top-level interface, it should be passed via the ControllerExtraConfig parameter which requires no template modifications at all.'}, {'account_id': 9410, 'date': '2015-09-25 14:55:27.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 9410, 'date': '2015-09-25 14:56:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Allow a deployer to specify HAProxy syslog server address

This commit aims to allow a deployer to specify where to send haproxy's
logs. It is backward compatible with what is already in place and send
the logs to the UNIX socket /dev/log

The value specified here will be written in the haproxy.cfg file with
the following behavior

HAProxySyslogAddress: 127.0.0.1 -> log 127.0.0.1 local0
HAProxySyslogAddress: ::1 -> log ::1 local0
HAProxySyslogAddress: /dev/log -> log /dev/log local0 (default)

Change-Id: I46c489a1f424e2219d129f332e64c64019aef850
Depends-On: If7f7c8154e544e5d8a49f79f642e1ad01644a66d

commit_message:
Retry on RetryRequest at API and RPC levels

Commit 80ee562dec3f397ea6c18a4ca3a1e69ab996341e added RetryRequest
to _ensure_default_security_group(), however one case where it is
called from within a transaction was missed.
Let's retry on request globally at API and RPC levels just like
it's currently done for DBDeadlocks to be more generic and
to cover all such missed and not missed cases at once.

Closes-Bug: #1505661
Change-Id: I951222368073b046c394d2c88ce5cb5188edfbea

commit_message:
Disk type for virtual environment must be SATA

Today we figured out that VirtIO disks are not treated as SCSI devices,
and thus are ignored by introspection.

Change-Id: Ib4bbf3abdb32b5a720a64fd12de5827e5e22a5e4

commit_message:
Add more informative error during parsing

If there is some error during parsing template or
env file, CSafeLoader errors doesn't contains snippet
from template. So, we need to use SafeLoader for more
informative error with snippet from parsed template.

Change-Id: I79039164533c032db66c933c4e8882b8942961eb
Related-bug: #1496361

once the new resources have been merged.

commit_message:
Allow LBaas integration tests to dynamically skip

lbaas v1 and v2 are mutually exclusive and cannot be enabled at the
same time within devstack.  The current integation test goes after the
existing lbaas v1 resources with a devstack setup with the
q-lbaas service.  This patch allow the test itself to
be smart enough to skip itself when the required lbaas version
is not available.

The current infra gate job template is hardcoded to only enable
lbaas v1 (q-lbaas), so the v1 test will continue to work properly
and the new v2 test (wip) will be dynamically skipped.

A follow up patch will modify the infra gate job template,
{pipeline}-heat-dsvm-functional-{engine}-{datastore}{branch-designator},
to also include an lbaas version.  Then the job can setup either
a lbaas v1 or v2 devstack so both tests can be run.

Another follow up patch will flush out the lbaas v2 integration test
once the new resources have been merged.

blueprint: lbaasv2-suport

Change-Id: I0e4c83f1b078451607a30e8b665e309ea5e170d1

Add instructions on how to add proxy configuration to Docker

commit_message:
clean requirements.txt

We have removed all rependency of openstack.common, but left
something in requirements.txt:

* we don't directly require posix-ipc
* we directly require six

We have extracted store related code to glance-store, but some
requirements are left:

* python-swiftclient
* oslo.vmware

We directly require Paste package, so there is no need to mention
kesytone related information. And python-keystoneclient is not
used any more, we are using the separated keystonemiddleware.

This patch updates requirements.txt according to above fact.

Change-Id: I320c0e6ad3787629041ddb6b5349ec5bc66b0f86
Depends-On: I5936a31b6233c2073c9aed8c6b0b18ffe31dc9b4

(1 comment)

just reviewed some of the changes made. my overall feeling is that this change is gonna be a huge one. If we want to enforce project_safe, we need to do it to all objects that have a 'project' field. This include all APIs to each object type. If will definitely result in a huge patch.

Another option to make this change is to split it into several patches, each of which focus on a particular object type. Make a COMPLETE change to that object in a single patch, then propose a different patch for another object type.

IMO, the net result of a partial change is introducing subtle bugs instead of fixing things."}, {'account_id': 15642, 'date': '2015-10-14 15:13:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Agreed... I think it's just going to be a significantly pervasive patch. Will be more manageable to break it up per object type. The current design will work fine I think."}, {'account_id': 11034, 'date': '2015-10-15 01:38:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Make all cluster DB queries project_safe

This patch makes all cluster realted DB queries project_safe by
default.

commit_message:
Check that docker-container runs successfully.

Break execution with error message in case if
the docker fails to start new container.

Change-Id: I2880a0a569dc3a56a73c0f9deea018f5b626ae10
Closes-bug: #1485758

commit_message:
Explicitly unset package update hooks when re-deploying

Because existing heat environment is used (instead of passing whole
environment with each stack-update command), it's possible
that there are some hooks left in the existing environment.

As a short-term solution, we make sure we unset hooks (which are
now set only by package update command).

Change-Id: I9782098fb4be889e63824338b2fdb6c9b1b13bf4
Depends-On: I1cb6c069cf6cf3b5f9504b35ca9538ba99ec405d
Closes-Bug: #1502869

commit_message:
Updated hostlayout to fix some wording

The change removes the documented "HARD" requirement to have
a physical load balancer which is absolutly not true when deploying
the project.

Change-Id: I9832a1f8fd67c148800a0062bbf8f264920cba5c
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Do not copy sources

We do not need to copy source files anymore with current
openstackdocstheme, unset html_show_sourcelink and html_copy_source
links. Report a bug works without these as well.

This reduces the amount of files we build and publish (for Install Guide
from 42 MB to 39 MB), and thus speeds up building (from 44 to 41s for
Install Guide) slightly.

Change-Id: I5d8f332aedd03ef1b2732bcfe01d2338f78fb29d

commit_message:
Spelling miss in Networking Guide

========================
We recommend using Open vSwitch with VLAN as segration.
This way you can combine normal VMs without SR-IOV ports
and instances with SR-IOV ports on a single neutron network.
========================
I changed" segration " to "segregation ".

Update the related RST files.
Closes-Bug: #1506693

Change-Id: I3ecd51a1213222b888927582db5748cbc4b98b4c

commit_message:
Delete previous template upon update

During stack update, we flip the stack raw_template a number of times.
In case of success, we leave the old active raw_template row unlinked to
anything, so it needs to be deleted. This patch does so.

Change-Id: I6f3ff5bfbac417e3bd6032cabfbc00bd6dec8b02
Closes-Bug: #1506077

commit_message:
Fixes POLL notification processing

Notification processing of POLL commands is currently broken.  This
fixes it by constructing the CRUD Event with a wildcard Resource.

Change-Id: I170743b2914feac1ead0c102028a5804f69b42d4
Closes-bug: #1505765

commit_message:
Merge tag '4.0.0'

This is a null-merge of the 4.0.0 release tag back into the master
branch so that the 4.0.0 tag will appear in the git commit history of
the master branch. It contains no actual changes to the master branch,
regardless of how our code review system's UI represents it. Please
ask in #openstack-infra if you have any questions, and otherwise try
to merge this as quickly as possible to avoid later conflicts on the
master branch.

Change-Id: Ida15251e735add79f9b495ab8da14bd952e053b9

[{'created': '2015-09-30 20:02:33.000000000', 'message': 'Update redstack to Fedora 22

A recent change provided a refresh of the Fedora support
in redstack and its elements for F21. F22 is actually the
current release, the DIB default cloud image, and now has
packages for percona-xtrabackup. This change proposes to:

- make dnf (instead of yum) the new default Fedora package
manager for redstack and the Trove elements
- update mysql and mariadb elements to make use of the
Fedora distro version of percona-xtrabackup
- undo some unfortunate hacks needed in F21 relating to
pip and the python-six library
- miscellaneous SSH file permission fixes for Fedora

As before, this change in itself does not necessarily
provide complete and tested dev images for ALL the current
datastores, but instead focuses on mysql 5.6 and mariadb 5.5.

Now, the DIB_RELEASE will default to 22 and a kick-start can
be issued as:
MYSQL_HOST=127.0.0.1 DISTRO=fedora ./redstack kick-start mysql

Change-Id: I5f195ea7e8ab4d5b8e97801d82d0897469c811d2
Closes-Bug: 1501485
'}]
commit_message:
Update redstack to Fedora 22

A recent change provided a refresh of the Fedora support
in redstack and its elements for F21. F22 is actually the
current release, the DIB default cloud image, and now has
packages for percona-xtrabackup. This change proposes to:

- make dnf (instead of yum) the new default Fedora package
manager for redstack and the Trove elements
- update mysql and mariadb elements to make use of the
Fedora distro version of percona-xtrabackup
- undo some unfortunate hacks needed in F21 relating to
pip and the python-six library
- miscellaneous SSH file permission fixes for Fedora

As before, this change in itself does not necessarily
provide complete and tested dev images for ALL the current
datastores, but instead focuses on mysql 5.6 and mariadb 5.5.

Now, the DIB_RELEASE will default to 22 and a kick-start can
be issued as:
MYSQL_HOST=127.0.0.1 DISTRO=fedora ./redstack kick-start mysql

Change-Id: I5f195ea7e8ab4d5b8e97801d82d0897469c811d2
Closes-Bug: 1501485

commit_message:
Merge tag '5.0.0'

This is a null-merge of the 5.0.0 release tag back into the master
branch so that the 5.0.0 tag will appear in the git commit history of
the master branch. It contains no actual changes to the master branch,
regardless of how our code review system's UI represents it. Please
ask in #openstack-infra if you have any questions, and otherwise try
to merge this as quickly as possible to avoid later conflicts on the
master branch.

Change-Id: Iccce01a30b9f1d1622c18834758e2470b936c7d9

[{'created': '2015-10-15 16:24:30.000000000', 'message': 'Fix DEFAULT_CONFIG_DIR

The current DEFAULT_CONFIG_DIR makes no sense
when installing tempest as a python package as it is
derived from the absolute path of config.py which is
incorrect.
For example:
/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/tempest/etc/
Is wrong.

Instead, it should be set to the relative path from
where the command is being executed.
For example, if tempest init ~/my_tempest were run,
the correct default config directory would be:
/home/me/my_tempest/etc
for the “my_tempest” initialized runtime.

Change-Id: I57d62107182ce652bbfb3c077b8a2311393234ed
'}]
commit_message:
Fix DEFAULT_CONFIG_DIR

The current DEFAULT_CONFIG_DIR makes no sense
when installing tempest as a python package as it is
derived from the absolute path of config.py which is
incorrect.
For example:
/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/tempest/etc/
Is wrong.

Instead, it should be set to the relative path from
where the command is being executed.
For example, if tempest init ~/my_tempest were run,
the correct default config directory would be:
/home/me/my_tempest/etc
for the “my_tempest” initialized runtime.

Change-Id: I57d62107182ce652bbfb3c077b8a2311393234ed

commit_message:
Move pxe._parse_instance_info() to deploy_utils

This commit moves function pxe._parse_instance_info() to
deploy_utils.py so that iLO drivers can use it.

Change-Id: If8092e5ae2ab9e0232fd595ee3be59b232ecb64c
Implements: blueprint new-boot-interface

commit_message:
Lower the log level for the message about concurrent port delete

There is nothing wrong or interesting in that log message that would be
useful during general cloud operation. It may be useful when debugging
an issue, so leaving the message, but with lowered log level.

Change-Id: I6c16a829665b602da84c0d694fcc5f8ad5ed546b

commit_message:
[www-ja] Publish Japanese Liberty documents

Update Japanese web page:
* publish Liberty Installation Guides
* publish latest Operations Guide
* simplify the contents
* modify Japanese description
* fix indentation as www/index.html

Change-Id: I8006c7c43724cf163e26a292914615f778fe497e

commit_message:
Done changes for LVM glossary reference

The definition for glossary term "Logical
Volume Manager" is already there in the glossary file.
So I just change the glossary reference from "LVM"
to "Logical Volume Manager"

Change-Id: I0b05fd4a20f9d84c3d0671d3fa95914163d97b4d
Closes-Bug: #1492253

commit_message:
Update RFE documentation to clarify when the tag is not appropriate

Adds a passage to clarify that the 'rfe' tag is not to be used for work
that is already well-defined, to avoid code being submitted before proper
discussion can take place.

Change-Id: I20a1a87b263154e8b7726da08bfb615b272ba4c1

commit_message:
Fix select all button in table view

This patch changes to using the $scope of the directive to access the
selected rows of the table. Also introduces a function to translate
the 'uuid' field returned from the magnum python client to 'id', this is
due to angular directives requiring a field called id in order to do
selection.

Closes-bug: #1506078

Change-Id: I9405f012cc18074484ee3dc19904a6ba51e9d1e7

[{'created': '2015-03-06 03:57:45.000000000', 'message': "Added call to retrieve the loadbalancer status tree

lbaas v2 implemented a status tree for a loadbalancer that shows
the statuses of all the children under a loadbalancer.  This enables
the client to also show this information with just the loadbalancer
name or id.  Since it's difficult to show a tree structure in table
format, the table has columns to show:
entity type
entity's id
entity's name
entity's parent id
entity's parent name
entity's provisioning status
entity's operating status

Change-Id: I47ace60e4f0cb604ba3f611a7dad6259b7bd6478
Partially-implements: blueprint lbaas-api-and-objmodel-improvement
"}]
commit_message:
Added call to retrieve the loadbalancer status tree

lbaas v2 implemented a status tree for a loadbalancer that shows
the statuses of all the children under a loadbalancer.  This enables
the client to also show this information with just the loadbalancer
name or id.  Since it's difficult to show a tree structure in table
format, the table has columns to show:
entity type
entity's id
entity's name
entity's parent id
entity's parent name
entity's provisioning status
entity's operating status

Change-Id: I47ace60e4f0cb604ba3f611a7dad6259b7bd6478
Partially-implements: blueprint lbaas-api-and-objmodel-improvement

commit_message:
Make 'grace_period' and 'destroy_after_deletion' work

Currently 'grace_period' and 'destroy_after_deletion' are not taking
effect for actions, this patch makes them working.
Fix one bug for cluster_scale_in action, in which 'count' is not set
correctly when policy is attached.

Change-Id: I52f71f259f793763ff1896ed6f25dcb2a601dee2

commit_message:
feat: add max_dispatches arg to conductor's run

- This will cause the conductor to only do 'n' number of dispatches,
  after which it stops dispatching jobs.

- This will allow the code that call the conductor, to monitor
  conductor.dispatching, and make a decision on what is to be done with
  it. Eg: Decomission a conductor, restart the conductor etc

- Backward Compatible.

Change-Id: I3386c7050806806b5ee44a74ba93e50515a5ab7b

subject: Do not spin when more processors than partitions
messages:
[{'account_id': 15799, 'date': '2015-10-01 15:30:21.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 15799, 'date': '2015-10-01 15:31:33.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-01 15:41:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-monasca-notification-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/60/229960/2/check/gate-monasca-notification-pep8/b8a5389/ : SUCCESS in 25s
- gate-monasca-notification-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/60/229960/2/check/gate-monasca-notification-python27/b264331/ : SUCCESS in 34s'}, {'account_id': 14273, 'date': '2015-10-01 17:15:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

What effect does releasing the partitions have on the rest of the notification system?  When you release are the other nodes thrown back into the renegotiation phase?'}, {'account_id': 15799, 'date': '2015-10-02 09:59:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> What effect does releasing the partitions have on the rest of the notification system? When you release are the other nodes thrown back into the renegotiation phase?

No; one process releasing does not make the others re-negotiate. If process A releases, then no other process will un-acquire. If process B then also releases (if it's shut down, for example) then process A will have the opportunity to acquire process B's partition.

(So, in fact, this is also fixing the bug that before this change, if a partition processor releases then it's released partition won't be picked up. There's also another bug here that if a processor terminates it doesn't release its partition...)"}, {'account_id': 15799, 'date': '2015-10-02 10:01:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

...if you want to convince yourself about this behaviour there's some demo code here; http://paste.openstack.org/show/475152/"}, {'account_id': 14273, 'date': '2015-10-02 14:03:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I may not get a chance to test this change out today but I should be able to soon.'}, {'account_id': 14273, 'date': '2015-10-02 14:04:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

"There's also another bug here that if a processor terminates it doesn't release its partition..."

Did you see this behaviour in your test environment?  It should absolutely repartition if a node dies and we've seen it do that in our HA environments.'}, {'account_id': 15799, 'date': '2015-10-02 15:37:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> Did you see this behaviour in your test environment?

No, that was just conjecture from reading the source. Having read up a bit more on how zookeeper locks work, I can see that explicitly leaving the set isn't needed.

The ideal fix here would probably be that if no partitions are allocated to block until a Partitioner state change. SetPartitioner does support triggering an Event on state change... however that would be fiddly to implement, as Python's Event implementation doesn't support automatic reset."}, {'account_id': 15799, 'date': '2015-10-02 16:51:00.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 15799, 'date': '2015-10-02 16:53:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

There's a toctou issue in there, but I think it's an improvement..."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-02 17:03:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-monasca-notification-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/60/229960/3/check/gate-monasca-notification-pep8/1e671d4/ : SUCCESS in 29s
- gate-monasca-notification-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/60/229960/3/check/gate-monasca-notification-python27/eace60c/ : SUCCESS in 31s'}, {'account_id': 12512, 'date': '2015-10-02 22:35:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

This seems like we are trying to fix a configuration issue with more code. The number of partitions should always be greater than the number of consumers. Adding more code to handle the case where there are less consumers than partitions seems to overly complicate things.'}, {'account_id': 15799, 'date': '2015-10-05 09:03:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

> This seems like we are trying to fix a configuration issue with more code.

First off, I don't think this is just a configuration issue. As far as I can see, with this fix in place having more consumers than partitions will allow the unused consumers to take over partitions if instances of monasca-notification terminate. That was the behaviour I guessed was intended, given the code currently in place.

Secondly, even if this is an issue that shouldn't occur with correct configuration, then given the lack of comprehensive documentation or guides on how to set up and configure Monasca, I don't think that a minor misconfiguration like this should result in a non-trivial use of resources keeping a CPU spinning. (And a consequent debug mission from operators.) If we're trying to encourage Monasca adoption, then "minor misconfiguration may burn up lots of CPU cycles, we don't consider that a bug" isn't a great message.'}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2015-10-07 02:11:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2015-10-07 02:13:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Seems like a good change for making the code more robust in the case of misconfiguration.'}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2015-10-16 02:31:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-16 02:31:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Verified

http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-16 02:34:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+2

[{'created': '2015-10-01 15:30:21.000000000', 'message': 'Do not spin when more processors than partitions

If monasca-notification is configured with more notification processors
than there are partitions in the corresponding topic then one or more of
the processor instances will not be allocated any partitions.

At present this results in the while loop spinning and wasting CPU
cycles. This change releases the partition. The SetPartitioner will then
wait for the default time_boundary (30 seconds). If the topic has gained
any partitions, or the partition allocation has been re-balanced, then
the processor will then be able to work. Otherwise the wait will repeat.

Change-Id: I55e8b1b52b704618cb35593f7bdfc1415d8b584d

then one or more of the processor instances will not be allocated

At present this results in the while loop spinning and wasting CPU
cycles. This change releases the partition. The SetPartitioner will
then wait for the default time_boundary (30 seconds). If the topic
has gained any partitions, or the partition allocation has been
re-balanced, then the processor will then be able to work. Otherwise
the wait will repeat.

Change-Id: I55e8b1b52b704618cb35593f7bdfc1415d8b584d
'}, {'created': '2015-10-02 16:51:00.000000000', 'message': 'Do not spin when more processors than partitions

If monasca-notification is configured with more notification
processors than there are partitions in the corresponding topic
then one or more of the processor instances will not be allocated
any partitions.

At present this results in the while loop spinning and wasting CPU
cycles. Instead, this change will block until the SetPartitioner
indicates that the state has changed, at which point the assigned
partitions will be re-evaluated.

Change-Id: I55e8b1b52b704618cb35593f7bdfc1415d8b584d
'}]
commit_message:
Do not spin when more processors than partitions

If monasca-notification is configured with more notification
processors than there are partitions in the corresponding topic
then one or more of the processor instances will not be allocated
any partitions.

At present this results in the while loop spinning and wasting CPU
cycles. Instead, this change will block until the SetPartitioner
indicates that the state has changed, at which point the assigned
partitions will be re-evaluated.

Change-Id: I55e8b1b52b704618cb35593f7bdfc1415d8b584d

commit_message:
Allow fetching oslo.config Opts from plugins

At the moment we only have access to the loading.Opts for a plugin,
which is fine most of the time but in places like auth_token middleware
we sometimes need to manually register a plugin options.

Extend the existing function to get the options from a Loader directly
if one is passed.

Change-Id: I3fd0cead78d5cc8ee2a3d19f056b5eff15208f84

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-12 23:49:12.000000000', 'message': "Use optional authentication

The last release of the kerberos plugin used optional authentication
that was removed as it seemed to be to simplify testing. After further
work it appears this reduces the amount of error messages that can be
received.

When connecting to a kerberos auth endpoint if an error message is
returned on authentication we can't assert the origin of that message
(as we haven't authenticated). Optional means we should accept the body
of these responses for debugging.

Change-Id: I026426cf983c0d7246a559d00f16bd59be804232
"}]
commit_message:
Use optional authentication

The last release of the kerberos plugin used optional authentication
that was removed as it seemed to be to simplify testing. After further
work it appears this reduces the amount of error messages that can be
received.

When connecting to a kerberos auth endpoint if an error message is
returned on authentication we can't assert the origin of that message
(as we haven't authenticated). Optional means we should accept the body
of these responses for debugging.

Change-Id: I026426cf983c0d7246a559d00f16bd59be804232

commit_message:
Document the os-attach-interfaces compute APIs in v2.1

The documentation exists in the v2 extension page:
http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref-compute-v2-ext.html#os-interface
but not in the V2.1 docs:
http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref-compute-v2.1.html
It looks like the wadl file is there, but its not linked from the chapter.

Closes-Bug: #1506545

Change-Id: I8fc867843bbcd07012eff928c952003684ecc84e

commit_message:
Fix a 409 failure on bay-update

The error is caused by change of user_token on bay-update. In
particular, when a bay is created, magnum pass user token to heat
as a parameter. Heat in term pass the token to each bay node via
user_data. When a bay is scaled up/down, another token is generated
and passed to heat, which changes the user_data of each bay nodes.
As a result, heat have to replace all the bay nodes to update the
user_data, which cause the error.

Change-Id: If3c3a0d435893d4fa4ed96f7ffd3c414200770f8
Closes-Bug: #1504689

commit_message:
Expose bind data via AccessInfo

The bind information is a standard part of the token data and can be
access from auth_token middleware so it should be exposed as part of the
AccessInfo object.

Change-Id: I45fc6eeed43f335aa1d771bdf1a11257432cb85c

commit_message:
Add url as a deprecated alias for endpoint

In order for us to transition python-openstackclient to keystoneauth,
we need a path forward so that people can move from using the in-tree
token-endpoint plugin to just using the admin-token plugin (which is the
thing that should be used for the bootstrapping-keystone usecase)

We could do fancy things in OCC to accomplish this (I have a patch) -
but instead of doing that, which is, as Dean says, really a layer
violation, why don't we just put url in here and be done with it.

Change-Id: Ia240d9599aad0c3e6727fcde451e3ddd21bc242f

commit_message:
Revert "Make OVS interface name hashing algorithm common and extend it"

Based on discussion with Ihar and Cedric, this may break upgrades. Let's
revert it for the time being and reassess.

This reverts commit 3d0db13370eee09aaee5923c54d0e3188509c4e5.

Change-Id: I69d74befb08e074c1bccd823cca0899de6ed57d6
Closes-Bug: 1504647

The requests package in pypi has it's own fork of urllib3 which is kept
in sync with snapshots of urllib3.  As of the latest requests package on
pypi (2.7.0), it's synced with urllib3 1.10.4 per [1] so we should also
cap urllib3 in g-r at that same version because it doesn't work with
urllib3 1.11.

This is also important to note since the distros don't handle packaging
requests in the same way.  For example, on Debian the forked urllib3
that's in the requests pip is left intact whereas on Fedora/CentOS/RHEL
the forked urllib3 package is removed so that python-requests just
depends on python-urllib3 from the distro.

So how this works really depends on if you're installing from pypi or a
distro, and if a distro, which distro and how they are handling things,
i.e. python-glanceclient from Fedora is actually going to require
python-urllib3 as a transitive dependency from python-requests, but on
Debian python-glanceclient only requires python-requests and it gets
urllib3 via the internal fork in the pip.

This isn't a problem in the gate since we're testing against Ubuntu and
pypi and have the requests with internal urllib3, but it causes issues
for anyone testing with packages from Fedora/CentOS/RHEL.

Related-Bug: #1476770

Change-Id: Iefeb9bc123f8c65fecd0cba585ecd3eb349b23a6

commit_message:
Cap urllib3 <=1.10.4 so it's synced up with requests 2.7.0

The requests package in pypi has it's own fork of urllib3 which is kept
in sync with snapshots of urllib3.  As of the 2.7.0 requests package,
it's synced with urllib3 1.10.4 per [1] so we should also
cap urllib3 in g-r at that same version because it doesn't work with
urllib3 1.11.

We cap requests<2.8 because of a regression in 2.8.0.

This is also important to note since the distros don't handle packaging
requests in the same way.  For example, on Debian the forked urllib3
that's in the requests pip is left intact whereas on Fedora/CentOS/RHEL
the forked urllib3 package is removed so that python-requests just
depends on python-urllib3 from the distro.

So how this works really depends on if you're installing from pypi or a
distro, and if a distro, which distro and how they are handling things,
i.e. python-glanceclient from Fedora is actually going to require
python-urllib3 as a transitive dependency from python-requests, but on
Debian python-glanceclient only requires python-requests and it gets
urllib3 via the internal fork in the pip.

This isn't a problem in the gate since we're testing against Ubuntu and
pypi and have the requests with internal urllib3, but it causes issues
for anyone testing with packages from Fedora/CentOS/RHEL.

[1] https://github.com/kennethreitz/requests/commit/ee7389da9

Related-Bug: #1476770
Closes-Bug: #1503768

Change-Id: Iefeb9bc123f8c65fecd0cba585ecd3eb349b23a6

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-13 15:05:30.000000000', 'message': 'Default ConvertedException code to 500

webob 1.5.0 released on 10/11 has change f6c749011 which
strictly enforces status codes in exceptions, and 0 is not
a valid status code so tests fail.

Change the default to 500 to match the default in the parent
class in webob.

Change-Id: If04eedb402092ca2cc307cb52f2231493c4375a2
Closes-Bug: #1505153
(cherry picked from commit 10438c0fc34bd088e018e1a5e8ec57b396528792)
'}, {'created': '2015-10-14 18:26:59.000000000', 'message': 'Default ConvertedException code to 500

webob 1.5.0 released on 10/11 has change f6c749011 which
strictly enforces status codes in exceptions, and 0 is not
a valid status code so tests fail.

Change the default to 500 to match the default in the parent
class in webob.

Closes-Bug: #1505153

commit_message:
Default ConvertedException code to 500

webob 1.5.0 released on 10/11 has change f6c749011 which
strictly enforces status codes in exceptions, and 0 is not
a valid status code so tests fail.

Change the default to 500 to match the default in the parent
class in webob.

Closes-Bug: #1505153
(cherry picked from commit 10438c0fc34bd088e018e1a5e8ec57b396528792)

-- Squashed with the following change to open kilo 2015.1.3 since they are
   co-dependent. --

Open Kilo 2015.1.3

Change-Id: Ic97696684c8545068597b4f1efd9d3eb19294d93

--

Change-Id: If04eedb402092ca2cc307cb52f2231493c4375a2

commit_message:
Make __all__ immutable

Using a mutable type implies that it's acceptable for the set of
publicly-accessible attributes to be mutated at runtime, which defeats
their intended purpose of documenting the public interface. Tuples are
immutable.

Change-Id: Ib3ab93224ba240040b08ece481ef5ba620c3f658

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-05 23:36:59.000000000', 'message': "Add SolidFire svip to config options

The SolidFire driver uses a simple method of gathering
the Storage Virtual IP, it just queries the Cluster and
asks for the SVIP. This is great almost all the time,
BUT it doesn't take into consideration that the deployer
may be using VLAN's and accessing the cluster from multiple
clouds, or multiple networks.

This patch just adds a config option to specify an SVIP
if the admin has configured VLANs in their environment and
on their cluster.  The default behavior is to still use the
global SVIP.

Closes-Bug: #1487194
(cherry picked from commit c11c7004ffcf3a5c739a4e076cd20554dd2ffc7d)

Conflicts:
	cinder/tests/test_solidfire.py

Change-Id: I10b784f903cd8d16580110f01d338a3ad867eada
"}, {'created': '2015-10-06 15:48:48.000000000', 'message': "Add SolidFire svip to config options

The SolidFire driver uses a simple method of gathering
the Storage Virtual IP, it just queries the Cluster and
asks for the SVIP. This is great almost all the time,
BUT it doesn't take into consideration that the deployer
may be using VLAN's and accessing the cluster from multiple
clouds, or multiple networks.

This patch just adds a config option to specify an SVIP
if the admin has configured VLANs in their environment and
on their cluster.  The default behavior is to still use the
global SVIP.

Closes-Bug: #1487194

commit_message:
Add SolidFire svip to config options

The SolidFire driver uses a simple method of gathering
the Storage Virtual IP, it just queries the Cluster and
asks for the SVIP. This is great almost all the time,
BUT it doesn't take into consideration that the deployer
may be using VLAN's and accessing the cluster from multiple
clouds, or multiple networks.

This patch just adds a config option to specify an SVIP
if the admin has configured VLANs in their environment and
on their cluster.  The default behavior is to still use the
global SVIP.

Closes-Bug: #1487194
(cherry picked from commit c11c7004ffcf3a5c739a4e076cd20554dd2ffc7d)

Conflicts:
	cinder/tests/test_solidfire.py

Change-Id: I10b784f903cd8d16580110f01d338a3ad867eada

commit_message:
remove unneeded call to getattr

This patch removes the unneeded call to getattr and removes the variable
assignment of the function name. This makes this code slightly more
readable. Note: I'm only making this change because the patch
(https://review.openstack.org/#/c/226686/) that introduced this code
introduced a small incompatibility to a few other plugins and
figured I'd clean this up.

TrivialFix

Change-Id: If175bdae0df3aa1f567b52b9dbd217fb55ec870b

commit_message:
Remove duplicates from the PROJECTS list

Duplicates in the PROJECTS list confuse workspace setup because the git
setup isn't idempotent. Easy fix for that is to remove duplicates and
only ever setup a repo once.

This will help us reduce the list of projects in the default PROJECTS
list because it will let us double account things during the transition.

Change-Id: I875641a5d00bc8afad97cbca6760ce66ac4a5c15

commit_message:
oslo.utils 2.6.0 causing tox test to hang

Forcing the change in requirements.txt is not feasible as all
entries there must match the global-requirements.txt file.
This forces a specific version of oslo.utils *before* the
requirements are loaded, thus ensuring that 2.6.0 is *not* used.

This should be considered a temporary fix only.

Change-Id: I4363c4b8b86efb15fd95d07ce6fff374024b3616
Partial-Bug: #1506402
Co-Authored-By: Amrith Kumar <amrith@tesora.com>

commit_message:
Bump oslo.utils to 2.4.0

The oslo.utils release for 2.4.0 has a base exception class
that tooz and taskflow can now share for there usage so it
would be great to bump the lower bound of oslo.utils so that
it can be used/incorporated.

Change-Id: I1b1325436ba5f81b311e8533289377ebb7842c4c

commit_message:
Deprecate event trait plugin 'split'

'split' plugin can be replaced by an jsonpath expresion
since jsonpath-rw-ext>=0.1.8.

This change deprecates it

Depends-On: I8cd971d6dd98cd6c4c3dc83696969c47e8cdd8ac
Change-Id: Iac2253c81dacaa1b2a2258569716d20916fc9920

Raise jsonpath-rw-ext version

This raises the jsonpath-rw-ext for ceilometer needs.

The change https://review.openstack.org/#/c/224493/ needs
a newer version of jsonpath-rw-ext to works.

commit_message:
Open port 6443 in security group for k8s bay

This should fix a SSLError, which is due to the blocking of the port.

Change-Id: I8cee3b4189bc84d095461abffefd969796ca7774
Closes-Bug: #1506226

commit_message:
Avoid wmi query while creating an acl

Wmi query is run everytime when a empty acl object is created.
This causes the time incurred to create and apply firewall rules
proportional to already existing ACLs in the WMI table.
Avoiding the query makes creation of ACL a constant function.

Fixes Bug: #1503630

Change-Id: I68a2d2590d7a17fa572662bf8ba25d84fc5a0d98

commit_message:
WIP: Replace Zookeeper sg driver with Tooz driver

Replace Zookeeper servicegroup driver with Tooz
equivalent zookeeper driver. The current
implementation of zookeeper servicegroup driver
is not functional. This patch uses Tooz Api's to
get member/group details and return back the
information to Nova API. New exceptions are also
added to translate tooz exceptions to relevant
Nova exceptions.

Change-Id: Ib9793bcc75f9e1e2ef6e3509dea71c3749b51bc5
Partially-Implements: bp tooz-for-service-groups

'}, {'created': '2015-10-15 18:29:02.000000000', 'message': "Switch to post-versioning

This combines 2 commits in order to pass the gate.

No longer mention next version on setup.cfg on stable branch.

Remove oslo.policy implementation tests from keystone

oslo.policy 0.12.0 contains a change to use requests to do the http
check rather than urllib. This change caused keystone tests to fail
because the keystone tests were mocking urllib, making assumptions
about how oslo.policy is implemented. Keystone doesn't need to test
internal features of oslo.policy, so these tests are removed.

Closes-Bug: 1505374
(cherry picked from commit 6016d017004acaae288312b196ef07ea98e9962d)

Change-Id: I75c44e88eb851a3b92a6d7d379d9a55e417703d6

commit_message:
Switch to post-versioning

This combines 2 commits in order to pass the gate.

No longer mention next version on setup.cfg on stable branch.

Remove oslo.policy implementation tests from keystone

oslo.policy 0.12.0 contains a change to use requests to do the http
check rather than urllib. This change caused keystone tests to fail
because the keystone tests were mocking urllib, making assumptions
about how oslo.policy is implemented. Keystone doesn't need to test
internal features of oslo.policy, so these tests are removed.

Closes-Bug: 1505374
(cherry picked from commit 6016d017004acaae288312b196ef07ea98e9962d)

Change-Id: I75c44e88eb851a3b92a6d7d379d9a55e417703d6

commit_message:
Neutron Post Install Uses Deprecated Keystone Client, Sets Needless Fact

neutron_post_install.yml uses the deprecated keystone client to fetch the
service tenant ID, and save it in a fact for presumably future use. But
upon further inspection, the fact is not even used anywhere anymore.

Change-Id: I32ec6df7161c28ec7007e9ad331a67e48884f80f
Closes-Bug: #1506574
(cherry picked from commit 4c2ae40bac39cba4d4551f1189b61309e5f4704a)

commit_message:
Add unmanage default implementation to VolumeDriver

Currently, only drivers that inherit from ManageableVD
get the default unmanage() implementation.

This is not correct, because drivers can support unmanage
without driver code.  Fix unmanage() in VolumeDriver to
support the LVM driver's unmanage operation.

(Regression from the refactoring done when introducing
abc classes.)

Closes-Bug: #1493544

Change-Id: Iaacf10141559a2c88b5873722d1e237dc9223f27
(cherry picked from commit bf22aeb185afe8de0db526c83e50c15113f84d88)
Conflicts:
	cinder/tests/test_volume.py

'}, {'created': '2015-10-07 13:06:44.000000000', 'message': "Adds pika RabbitMQ client library

It is necessary because oslo.messaging team is
developing pika-rabbitmq driver

- Is the library actively maintained?

Yes, last release in September, fairly recent commits, 241
contributors.

- Is the library good code?

It's recommended by RabbitMQ developers, Its code is well
organized.

- Is the library python 3 compatible?

Yes.

- Is the library license compatible?

Yes, BSD.

- Is the library already packaged in the distros we target (Ubuntu
  latest / Fedora latest)?

Yes.

- Is the function of this library already covered by other libraries
  in ``global-requirements.txt``?

Yes. Kombu is amqp client too, but this one is better maintained and
recommended by RabbitMQ developers 

Change-Id: I6cc1c98e84f45b4b09dcd74b9562969d70112826

commit_message:
Adds pika RabbitMQ client library

It is necessary because oslo.messaging team is
developing pika-rabbitmq driver

Change-Id: I6cc1c98e84f45b4b09dcd74b9562969d70112826
Partial-Implements: bp rabbit-pika

commit_message:
More info in RequestContext

The OpenStack standard log format string contains fields for
user ID, project ID, etc., that will be displayed if the
appropriate fields are set in the RequestContext. This change sets
the fields in the RequestContext.

Closes-Bug: 1500222
Change-Id: I4ae6da483cfae98f910a2905e80b6af606ae6468

So, maybe this is a bit early since we have two failing tests (currently skipped). Still, this is needed to enable functional testing in the gates...'}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-10-06 15:14:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Can you describe why it's a prerequisite for gating? Do you have a specific issue in mind?"}, {'account_id': 8122, 'date': '2015-10-06 15:18:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

It seems like enabling dsvm-functional with Python 3 will require having both "export PYTHON3=True" and Python 3 classifiers in setup.cfg. At least it is what is written at https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Python3#Functional_tests .'}, {'account_id': 14033, 'date': '2015-10-06 15:24:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-10-06 15:26:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I believe there may be some difference in what Doug assumes functional test suite is and what neutron has. In neutron, we don't rely on devstack to START our services, we do it inside the python interpreter that is invoked by tox target. So I am not sure it's needed to mark it for py34 right now, we can try it without it."}, {'account_id': 8122, 'date': '2015-10-06 15:31:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

What exactly is gate-neutron-dsvm-functional then ?'}, {'account_id': 8122, 'date': '2015-10-06 15:46:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

And do you just have to run "tox -efunctional" to run the functional tests? Is it done by Jenkins when a new patch is sent? If so, what is corresponding the check/gate name?'}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-10-06 15:52:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

To replicate what gate does, you need tox -e dsvm-functional, not functional.

The target uses devstack only to install the dependencies (f.e. openvswitch). Devstack does not start services. They are actually not started when running functional suite at all (their main() functions are not triggered; instead, agent classes are instantiated thru testr, and executed as any unit test, just with no mocks).'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-06 16:57:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

commit_message:
Cache the User's Project by Token ID

Project list fetched for each request. The patches caches the
project list and uses the token as the key in the cache. When
the user logout or switch project, the project list is removed
from the cache.

Change-Id: I2386d7a342cf02a0252e97cc48c5349ccab8a9eb
Closes-bug: 1241838

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-22 01:21:59.000000000', 'message': "Introduces advanced service drivers to akanda-appliance

This introduces the ability to create service manager drivers to handle
managing advanced services within the akanda-appliance.

It splits some common things into a System manager.  Existing
stuff that is router-specific is moved to a Router manager and we begin
implementing LBAAS drivers using Nginx.

We could and should work on the API for this.  Currently, our v1
API is entirely router-specific.  This adds to that and allows the
RUG to attach other advanced service configuratino data to the config
object it pushes.  If the corresponding service's driver has been enabled
in the appliance, it will attempt to find that data and configure the
advanced service accordingly.  Ideally, longterm we want a v2 API
that can reference all services the same.  There's a few ugly compat
hacks added here to maintain compatability with where the RUG expects
certain router resources to be.  We can evolve this over time.

Change-Id: I6048789ec15fad1dbc899cbbd82508433cb96d44
Partially-implements: blueprint appliance-provisioning-driver
"}, {'created': '2015-09-22 05:49:47.000000000', 'message': "Introduces advanced service drivers to akanda-appliance

This introduces the ability to create service manager drivers to handle
managing advanced services within the akanda-appliance.

stuff that is router-specific is moved to a Router manager and we begin

We could and should work on the API for this.  Currently, our v1
API is entirely router-specific.  This adds to that and allows the
RUG to attach other advanced service configuratino data to the config
object it pushes.  If the corresponding service's driver has been enabled
in the appliance, it will attempt to find that data and configure the
advanced service accordingly.  Ideally, longterm we want a v2 API
that can reference all services the same.  There's a few ugly compat

certain router resources to be.  We can evolve this over time.

commit_message:
Introduces advanced service drivers to akanda-appliance

This introduces the ability to create service manager drivers to handle
managing advanced services within the akanda-appliance.

It splits some common things into a System manager.  Existing
stuff that is router-specific is moved to a Router manager and we begin
implementing LBAAS drivers using Nginx.

At the moment, configuration for which drivers are loaded by the appliance
code itself is stored in /etc/default/akanda-appliance.  This is setup by
a DIB_* variable and accessed by the appliance via environment variable. We
should improve this later when we need to expose richer configuration to the
appliance.

We could and should work on the API for this.  Currently, our v1
API is entirely router-specific.  This adds to that and allows the
RUG to attach other advanced service configuratino data to the config
object it pushes.  If the corresponding service's driver has been enabled
in the appliance, it will attempt to find that data and configure the
advanced service accordingly.  Ideally, longterm we want a v2 API
that can reference all services the same.  There's a few ugly compat
hacks added here to maintain compatability with where the RUG expects
certain router resources to be.  We can evolve this over time.

Partially-implements: blueprint appliance-provisioning-driver
Depends-on: Ic19a883f56fb6d65a83b1f4d93b581f9e242d97f
Change-Id: I6048789ec15fad1dbc899cbbd82508433cb96d44

commit_message:
Mask passwords when logging the HTTP response

We should sanitize the response body before logging to make sure we
aren't leaking through credentials like in the case of the response from
the os-initialize_connection volume API.

Closes-Bug: #1490693

NOTE(mriedem): The test is slightly different in kilo because the
_http_log_response method requires kwargs.

Change-Id: Ifd95d3fb624b4636fb72cc11762af62e00a026a0
(cherry picked from commit 3e26ff824801d5084791a52980021784e794e35f)

commit_message:
Merge tag '7.0.0'

This is a null-merge of the 7.0.0 release tag back into the master
branch so that the 7.0.0 tag will appear in the git commit history of
the master branch. It contains no actual changes to the master branch,
regardless of how our code review system's UI represents it. Please
ask in #openstack-infra if you have any questions, and otherwise try
to merge this as quickly as possible to avoid later conflicts on the
master branch.

Change-Id: I920a33126a5871447602e6f9872985d8c9a4707a

Most of my inline comments are minor nits.

I like the overall idea of having two standardized keys, one as a vendor specific identifier for the array and the other for the host (if managed). I think my only question is do we need to explicitly set managed_backend_name to None if we are using unmanaged? It might just be easiest to leave it out. Thoughts? Overall I think this a goos solution though.'}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2015-10-12 23:25:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Update config format for replication_devices

The first pass at setting up config entries for
replication targets was a hacky custom string parser
with its own unique syntax.

A better option is to use oslo.cfg's MultiOpt in conjunction
with Dict types so we can eliminate quite a bit of custom
parsing and most importantly use a standard syntax for conf
entries to make things easy for admins and reduce the
probability of syntax errors and mistakes in config setttings.

Change-Id: Ie300c1f1db548d258906eebbcea8265583086468
Closes-Bug: #1504696

commit_message:
Add agent_amt docs

This adds documentation for the new agent_amt driver, and clarifies that
the pxe_amt deploys over iSCSI.

commit_message:
Merge tag '5.0.0'

This is a null-merge of the 5.0.0 release tag back into the master
branch so that the 5.0.0 tag will appear in the git commit history of
the master branch. It contains no actual changes to the master branch,
regardless of how our code review system's UI represents it. Please
ask in #openstack-infra if you have any questions, and otherwise try
to merge this as quickly as possible to avoid later conflicts on the
master branch.

Change-Id: Iac5daec1713c3251447d2353edbfe2a317fb19ef

Script for running unit, func and probe tests at once

When developing Swift it's often needed to run all tests.
This script makes it much simpler.

commit_message:
caret button shouldn't be disabled

Currently, in action dropdown menu with split-button, when the action
disabled, the caret button is disabled as well, this cause it's
impossible to interact with other actions in the dropdown. Caret button
should be always enabled.

Change-Id: Iff9ddfe4172d10e8550b535666d9638ce7638b0f
Closes-Bug: #1505863

commit_message:
Dump browser log on integration test failure

Having all messages from browser console inside a test log sometimes
may be very valuable in understanding the cause of test failure.

Change-Id: I9ef39e412e0b9f1faacf0a3e42418ca138c52d66
Related-Bug: #1505320

commit_message:
Merge tag '8.0.0'

This is a null-merge of the 8.0.0 release tag back into the master
branch so that the 8.0.0 tag will appear in the git commit history of
the master branch. It contains no actual changes to the master branch,
regardless of how our code review system's UI represents it. Please
ask in #openstack-infra if you have any questions, and otherwise try
to merge this as quickly as possible to avoid later conflicts on the
master branch.

Change-Id: I9e345994ed5c26792b86809000161a5384eaea28

commit_message:
Include alembic versions directory to the package

If package is built without access to git metadata, all the migration
scripts are not included in the build. We need to explicitly specify to
package the scripts.

This patch also removes non-existing files from MANIFEST.in

Change-Id: I9a2acad13271863ee94de63c2404e8697ea70601
Related-bug: #1505628

commit_message:
Add note about driver API breakage

This adds a note about the breakage we caused to our driver API behavior
during Liberty, and resolutions that out of tree drivers may use to fix
themselves.

See also:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-October/076205.html

Change-Id: I2671e7c8634f3fd3115697df6f0cab68c589d21d
Closes-Bug: #1502980

have you considered enable_plugin mechanism?'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-03-03 13:07:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

this should be done as an external devstack plugin'}, {'account_id': 10635, 'date': '2015-03-04 18:28:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

We have considered using the "enable_plugin" option. The drawback is that anyone wishing to use our agent would have to know the exact git repository, add the entry in the config and get through all these details.

Using the proposed option will help anyone wishing to use the latest version of the agent to do so without having to dig into all these details. 

Since the hyper-v agent is still going to be part of neutron (as part of the decomposition), we have also chosen this approach based on the existing thrid-party extensions, seeing the way ryu, trema and midonet did it. 

We think that relying only on the "enable_plugin" will require any potential user dig into unnecessary level of details.'}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2015-03-10 11:47:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 10635, 'date': '2015-10-15 20:48:50.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Adds networking_hyperv as a neutron third party driver

This commit adds the configuration file necessary for
devstack to be able to clone the stackforge repo for
the project. In order to do so, users will have to add
the following line in their local.conf file:

enable_service networking_hyperv

This commit is useful for users that have configured
devstack to use the ML2 neutron plugin and 'hyperv' as a
mechanism driver and wish to be up to date with the changes.
This is particularly useful for the Hyper-V CI.

Stackforge repo: https://github.com/stackforge/networking-hyperv

Change-Id: Ice93371c39abac5e3783f988ac38865bcb471294

commit_message:
Ignore non release versions when publishing latest docs

Ignore alpha, beta, rc versions when determining if we are publishing
the latest version of a projects documentation. These pre release
versions will still publish to /developer/project/$version but won't
update the root location of /developer/project.

This works around an issue with sort -V sorting the alphas, betas, and
rcs higher than the actual release. It also arguable better represents
what we want to do when publishing the latest of a release.

Change-Id: I2a4cd00414dee2e8307c681ed2bc6b61f7c670d6

commit_message:
Enable POST samples API when gnocchi enabled

Currently, if we enabled gnocchi, the every API of meters, resources,
samples will be disabled and 410 response will be returned. The posting
samples API shouldn't be diabled.

Change-Id: I142e4470a69a0782cabb6b1b4160faac0d48f0df

  resources
- Set the default log level of neutronclient to INFO to avoid recording

commit_message:
Clean some log messages when polling neutron resources

- Handle the regular resource not found warnings when polling neutron
  resources
- Set the default log level of neutronclient to INFO to avoid recording
  requests of neutronclient token issuing.

Change-Id: I94836b3031bae5bee2634b301c67a0c9487112ac
Closes-Bug: #1504396

commit_message:
Simplify the validation of required fields of pipeline source

- The required field "meters" (or "counters") validation is invalid
- The validation of these required fields of SampleSource and EventSource
  are unnecessary

Change-Id: Ifda35d7ff0e5baa1a97017d9deb6db7613fb8e31

commit_message:
Fix a missing detail in install guide.

Need to have '-p' option for 'mkdir' command as it could be
creating parent directories.

Change-Id: I4cc11c8f24c91f862f4efc4c0e76a44dc88d2b8e

of projects expected.  Trying to document them all is madness, but
at least document the expected numbers.  LDAP will not support
a project for the domain, but SQL will, and there are tests that mix
both together.

This patch partially implements Reseller.

Previous patches did:
  - Add is_domain field in Project Table
  - Change project name constraint

This patch reflects any domain operation on the
project table, mapping domains to projects that
have the is_domain attribute set to True.

In addition, it changes the read operations to use only the project table.

Now, the root projects will only be is_domain projects, so, if the user
does not pass a parent_id to a non is_domain project, its parent_id will
be set to his domain_id.

Next patches will:
  - Migrate domains to project table (and drop domain table)

'}, {'created': '2015-03-12 12:54:33.000000000', 'message': 'Honor domain operations in project table

This patch partially implements Reseller.

Previous patches did:
  - Add is_domain field in Project Table
  - Change project name constraint

This patch reflects any domain operation on the project table, mapping domains
to projects that have the is_domain attribute set to True.
In addition, it changes the read operations to use only the project table.

The migration script creates an is_domain project on the project table for each
domain in the domain table. The existing root projects will be child of the
domain. The is_domain projects will be roots. If the user tries to
create a non is_domain project without passing the parent_id, it will
be set to its domain_id.

Next patches will:
  - Remove all domain table references and drop domain table

This patch reflects any domain operation on the project table, mapping domains
to projects that have the is_domain attribute set to True.
In addition, it changes the read operations to use only the project table.

The migration script creates an is_domain project on the project table for each
domain in the domain table. The existing root projects will be child of the
domain. The is_domain projects will be roots. If the user tries to
create a non is_domain project without passing the parent_id, it will
be set to its domain_id.

Co-Authored-By: Henrique Truta <henrique@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>
Co-Authored-By: Hugo Nicodemos <hugonicodemos@gmail.com>

Co-Authored-By: Samuel de Medeiros Queiroz <samuel@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>

Partially-Implements: bp reseller

child of the domain.

commit_message:
Honor domain operations in project table

Reflects all domain operation on the project table, mapping domains
to projects that have the is_domain attribute set to True. It also changes
the read operations to use only the project table.

The domain table references will be removed in this follow-up patch:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/165936/

Co-Authored-By: Henrique Truta <henrique@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>
Co-Authored-By: Raildo Mascena <raildo@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>
Co-Authored-By: Rodrigo Duarte <rodrigods@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>
Co-Authored-By: Samuel de Medeiros Queiroz <samuel@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>

Partially-Implements: bp reseller

Change-Id: I8bdff22e20d672d05a732723c9a35f87ba0f0063

commit_message:
Fix ensure_cache to always refresh cache

It looks like this bit was lost in a rebase of 220345.  This
is required to properly detect backing instances have gone away.

Change-Id: I630ab9fe0b2e343051e69ae19ca6bb548d12364e

commit_message:
Don't log an error in ovsdb commands.

These exceptions are not always errors.  Sometimes it's expected and the
exceptions are handled gracefully.  Let the errors get logged elsewhere
if it's a real error.
