[{'created': '2015-09-28 18:28:13.000000000', 'message': 'Add flat provider network support.

This patch adds support for flat provider networks.  VLAN support will
be added next, but the first step was to get flat provider network
support working end to end.

For more information about how this works in OVN, see this commit:

https://github.com/openvswitch/ovs/commit/c02819293d52f7ea7b714242d871b2b01f57f905

You can test this in devstack by doing the following steps:

1) Create a dummy bridge.

    $ ovs-vsctl add-br br-provider

2) Configure ovn-controller with a bridge mapping that maps the network
   "providernet"

    $ ovs-vsctl set open . \
    external-ids:ovn-bridge-mappings=providernet:br-provider

Observe that ovn-controller automatically created patch ports between
br-int and br-provider.

    $ ovs-vsctl show

3) Create a Neutron provider network.

    $ neutron net-create provider --shared \
    --provider:physical_network providernet \
    --provider:network_type flat

4) Create a Neutron port on the provider network.

    $ neutron port-create provider

Observe that the OVN plugin created a special logical switch that models
the connection between this port and the provider network.

    $ ovn-nbctl show
    ...
     lswitch 5bbccbbd-f5ca-411b-bad9-01095d6f1316 (neutron-729dbbee-db84-4a3d-afc3-82c0b3701074)
         lport provnet-729dbbee-db84-4a3d-afc3-82c0b3701074
             macs: unknown
         lport 729dbbee-db84-4a3d-afc3-82c0b3701074
             macs: fa:16:3e:20:38:d1
    ...

    $ ovn-nbctl lport-get-type provnet-729dbbee-db84-4a3d-afc3-82c0b3701074
    localnet

    $ ovn-nbctl lport-get-options provnet-729dbbee-db84-4a3d-afc3-82c0b3701074
    network_name=providernet

Related-bug: #1474977
Change-Id: I9bbd51e8f8c0e16d6a2cdb54ae0979889bf73dcc
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>
'}, {'created': '2015-10-04 10:48:06.000000000', 'message': 'Add provider network support.

This patch adds support for flat and vlan provider networks using the
standard Neutron provider networks API extension.

For more information about how this works in OVN, see these commits:

https://github.com/openvswitch/ovs/commit/c02819293d52f7ea7b714242d871b2b01f57f905
https://github.com/openvswitch/ovs/commit/779e72cc57a106251cc9e6696e8c9aabb56d30b5

or go through this OVN tutorial to the "locally attached networks"
sections:

https://github.com/openvswitch/ovs/blob/master/tutorial/OVN-Tutorial.md

You can test this in devstack by doing the following steps:

1) Create a dummy bridge.

    $ ovs-vsctl add-br br-provider

2) Configure ovn-controller with a bridge mapping that maps the network
   "providernet"

    $ ovs-vsctl set open . \
    external-ids:ovn-bridge-mappings=providernet:br-provider

Observe that ovn-controller automatically created patch ports between
br-int and br-provider.

    $ ovs-vsctl show

3) Create a Neutron provider network.

    $ neutron net-create provider --shared \
    --provider:physical_network providernet \
    --provider:network_type flat

or

    $ neutron net-create provider-101 --shared \
    --provider:physical_network providernet \
    --provider:network_type vlan \
    --provider:segmentation_id 101

4) Create a Neutron port on the provider network.

    $ neutron port-create provider

or

    $ neutron port-create provider-101

Observe that the OVN plugin created a special logical switch that models
the connection between this port and the provider network.

    $ ovn-nbctl show
    ...
     lswitch 5bbccbbd-f5ca-411b-bad9-01095d6f1316 (neutron-729dbbee-db84-4a3d-afc3-82c0b3701074)
         lport provnet-729dbbee-db84-4a3d-afc3-82c0b3701074
             macs: unknown
         lport 729dbbee-db84-4a3d-afc3-82c0b3701074
             macs: fa:16:3e:20:38:d1
    ...

    $ ovn-nbctl lport-get-type provnet-729dbbee-db84-4a3d-afc3-82c0b3701074
    localnet

    $ ovn-nbctl lport-get-options provnet-729dbbee-db84-4a3d-afc3-82c0b3701074
    network_name=providernet

Related-bug: #1474977
Change-Id: I9bbd51e8f8c0e16d6a2cdb54ae0979889bf73dcc
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

https://github.com/openvswitch/ovs/blob/master/tutorial/OVN-Tutorial.md

You can test this in devstack by doing the following steps:

1) Create a dummy bridge.

    $ ovs-vsctl add-br br-provider

2) Configure ovn-controller with a bridge mapping that maps the network
   "providernet"

    $ ovs-vsctl set open . \
    external-ids:ovn-bridge-mappings=providernet:br-provider

Observe that ovn-controller automatically created patch ports between
br-int and br-provider.

    $ ovs-vsctl show

3) Create a Neutron provider network.

    $ neutron net-create provider --shared \
    --provider:physical_network providernet \
    --provider:network_type flat

or

    $ neutron net-create provider-101 --shared \
    --provider:physical_network providernet \
    --provider:network_type vlan \
    --provider:segmentation_id 101

4) Create a Neutron port on the provider network.

    $ neutron port-create provider

or

    $ neutron port-create provider-101

Observe that the OVN plugin created a special logical switch that models
the connection between this port and the provider network.

    $ ovn-nbctl show
    ...
     lswitch 5bbccbbd-f5ca-411b-bad9-01095d6f1316 (neutron-729dbbee-db84-4a3d-afc3-82c0b3701074)
         lport provnet-729dbbee-db84-4a3d-afc3-82c0b3701074
             macs: unknown
         lport 729dbbee-db84-4a3d-afc3-82c0b3701074
             macs: fa:16:3e:20:38:d1
    ...

    $ ovn-nbctl lport-get-type provnet-729dbbee-db84-4a3d-afc3-82c0b3701074
    localnet

    $ ovn-nbctl lport-get-options provnet-729dbbee-db84-4a3d-afc3-82c0b3701074
    network_name=providernet

Related-bug: #1474977
Change-Id: I9bbd51e8f8c0e16d6a2cdb54ae0979889bf73dcc
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Add provider network support.

This patch adds support for flat and vlan provider networks using the
standard Neutron provider networks API extension.  The document on
testing with devstack has also been updated to cover how to test
provider networks.

For more information about how this works in OVN, see these commits:

https://github.com/openvswitch/ovs/commit/c02819293d52f7ea7b714242d871b2b01f57f905
https://github.com/openvswitch/ovs/commit/779e72cc57a106251cc9e6696e8c9aabb56d30b5

or go through this OVN tutorial to the "locally attached networks"
sections:

https://github.com/openvswitch/ovs/blob/master/tutorial/OVN-Tutorial.md

Related-bug: #1474977
Change-Id: I9bbd51e8f8c0e16d6a2cdb54ae0979889bf73dcc
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Neutron Post Install Uses Deprecated Keystone Client, Sets Needless Fact

neutron_post_install.yml uses the deprecated keystone client to fetch the
service tenant ID, and save it in a fact for presumably future use. But
upon further inspection, the fact is not even used anywhere anymore.

Change-Id: I32ec6df7161c28ec7007e9ad331a67e48884f80f
Closes-Bug: #1506574

commit_message:
Add debug logging for DB retry attempt.

That should help to debug DB contentions.
Right now it's not clear from the logs if or how often reconnects
are triggered.

Change-Id: I8c9c95c262e69d9aa97294abe7fbfb31b1b18c5d

commit_message:
Replace assertTrue(a in b) with assertIn(a, b)

Since python2.6 is no more supported, replacing
assertTrue(a in b) with assertIn(a, b) can be done.
This will give better message during the test failure
as a bonus.

Change-Id: Ie0c13f3b1db1e9ac728f9af102fce6999ba687f3

commit_message:
Remove selenium job from stable branches

The horizon selenium tests are only working on master. The job was
recently made voting. Since they continue to fail on stable branches,
we need to not run them on stable branches.

Change-Id: I888ce0358891ca73deb8bebe4ca5e47b48925f19

commit_message:
Python 3: skip test_json_with_utf8 on Py3

The last skipped unit test should indeed be skipped: it does not make
sense to run it with Python 3.

$ python 2
>>> import json; json.dumps({'a': u'\xe9'.encode('utf-8')})
'{"a": "\\u00e9"}'

$ python3
>>> import json; json.dumps({'a': u'\xe9'.encode('utf-8')})
Traceback (most recent call last):
  ...
  File "/usr/lib64/python3.4/json/encoder.py", line 173, in default
    raise TypeError(repr(o) + " is not JSON serializable")
TypeError: b'\xc3\xa9' is not JSON serializable

In Python 2, the JSON encoder function to encode a string begins with
a magic test to convert UTF-8 encoded string to Unicode:

    if isinstance(s, str) and HAS_UTF8.search(s) is not None:
        s = s.decode('utf-8')

https://hg.python.org/cpython/file/4188cd5dc0c5/Lib/json/encoder.py#l42

This trick is gone in Python 3:

https://hg.python.org/cpython/file/288953a787ce/Lib/json/encoder.py#l49

Change-Id: Iddaaea4ebedf04c87f1ff9f9098163a15ffa78f7
Blueprint: neutron-python3
Closes-Bug: #1491824

The easiest way to reproduce it is to run a scenario that includes an expected failure. A simple example would to be to set your instances quota to 10, boot ten instances, then boot an 11th instance in a try-except block, where the expected condition of that _boot_server() call is failure. That's not the same case. In that case, the entire iteration fails if one of the atomic actions fails. In the case I'm talking about (and in the test data that I added), the failure is expected so one atomic action fails while the entire iteration succeeds."}, {'account_id': 6172, 'date': '2015-10-11 02:18:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Chris, 

Such situation must be impossible. 

I mean iteration is marked as failed if scenario method rise exception. 
So there can't be failed *atomic* and not failed *iteration* except the case when scenario is written not properly and creates different amount of atomic actions on each call."}, {'account_id': 11748, 'date': '2015-10-12 11:15:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

It's possible if one atomic timer fails and the exception is caught because it's expected, as in the original example I gave of deliberately exceeding the instances quota. You could write that as something like:

    def my_check_instance_quota(self, ...):
        self._boot_servers(image, flavor, 1, instances_amount=10)
        try:
            self._boot_server(image, flavor)
        except Exception:
            pass
        else:
            raise Exception("Unexpectedly able to exceed instances quota")

There are always exactly two atomic timers, but in the case where the iteration succeeds, one timer succeeds and one fails. I know this crosses over a bit from pure benchmarking into functional testing, but until 294f00b it worked fine.'}, {'account_id': 11748, 'date': '2015-10-14 19:24:51.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 11748, 'date': '2015-10-14 19:25:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Handle tracebacks in chart generation

If a single atomic action fails in an iteration that succeeds overall
-- i.e., an expected failure -- then chart generation raises two
uncaught exceptions. This adds try-except logic to handle them and
produce a sensible chart. It also adds a dummy scenario to test this
case.

Change-Id: I33926a66918c6cbef9b6a87d25a3c7c027572e10

commit_message:
Add testresources used by oslo.db fixture

If we use oslo.db fixtures, we'll need the package or
the next version of oslo.db release will break us.

manually picked from: I176c85551007d3d9e7de8896ad12e9b87ff278d8
for more information see: I1e06e77308a7dd23209124f0807d61fb52470188

Change-Id: Ib511ec705206b2168fe18f5870ca81d59b7ba89f
Closes-Bug: 1503501
(cherry picked from commit a7ecd00a99fc26dce1e210d7e67e03efe752b5d3)

commit_message:
Caches switch port, VLAN, VSID setting data WMI objects

The Hyper-V Neutron Agent, during its first loop, will iterate
over all the switch ports, checking their proper setup. In order
to avoid wasting time querying the necessary WMI objects for each
port, they are cached first.

Initialises the cache for the mentioned objects. Thus, they will be
retrieved from the cache while processing 'foo' port.

This will also improve the general performance of the agent.

Partial-Bug: #1505196

Change-Id: I5a70600ffdb1aa29d113972f13485bbbb3138a47

commit_message:
trim requirements for ksc

these requirements are no longer required since they are no longer
used

also remove oslo.serialization since is now includes msgpack libs,
and we're only using it for tests

commit_message:
Fix oslo.messaging+zmq+dsvm to run from master

gate-tempest-dsvm-full-zmq ends up using oslo.messaging from
pip. We need a job that runs dsvm-full with oslo.messaging from git.

Change-Id: If85ce9e4a6c976f30f29671e7d23eff784d0f5b8

[{'created': '2015-10-13 14:39:25.000000000', 'message': 'Fix random miss in comsumer/publisher broker

The error in bug report is comfirmed but reproduced randomly. Runing [0]
100 times and you could get about 3 failures on average. The reason is
that publisher finished between L39 and L40 here [1].

Before this patch, we are starting comsumers first and then publisher.
Before publisher doing publish(), comsumer threads are in while-true
loop because the thread event is_published is not setted. At the moment
publish work has been done, which means the is_published is setted,
each comsumer thread could be in any position of the while-true loop. If
it happens between L39 and L40, the broker will miss the job. If there
is only one comsumer here (it is in our test case), the miss happens.

To clarify it:

39    while True:
40        if not queue:
        <<< this moment, publisher finished >>>
        <<< which means queue is not empty >>>
        <<< and is_published is setted. >>>
41            if is_published.isSet():
42                break
43            time.sleep(0.1)
44            continue
45        else:
46            try:
47                args = queue.popleft()
48            except IndexError:
49                # consumed by other thread
50                continue

To fix this is very simple: do publish job BEFORE the comsumers start :)

[0] tox -e py27
tests.unit.plugins.openstack.context.keystone.test_users.UserGeneratorTestCase.test_users_and_tenants_in_context
[1]
https://github.com/openstack/rally/blob/master/rally/common/broker.py#L39-L40

commit_message:
Fix random miss in comsumer/publisher broker

The error in bug report is comfirmed but reproduced randomly. Runing [0]
100 times and you could get about 3 failures on average. The reason is
that publisher finished between L39 and L40 here [1].

Before this patch, we are starting comsumers first and then publisher.
Before publisher doing publish(), comsumer threads are in while-true
loop because the thread event is_published is not setted. At the moment
publish work has been done, which means the is_published is setted,
each comsumer thread could be in any position of the while-true loop. If
it happens between L39 and L40, the broker will miss the job. If there
is only one comsumer here (it is in our test case), the miss happens.

To clarify it:

39    while True:
40        if not queue:
        <<< this moment, publisher finished >>>
        <<< which means queue is not empty >>>
        <<< and is_published is setted. >>>
41            if is_published.isSet():
42                break
43            time.sleep(0.1)
44            continue
45        else:
46            try:
47                args = queue.popleft()
48            except IndexError:
49                # consumed by other thread
50                continue

To fix this is very simple: do publish job BEFORE the comsumers start
and remove the unrequired is_published :)

[0] tox -e py27
tests.unit.plugins.openstack.context.keystone.test_users.UserGeneratorTestCase.test_users_and_tenants_in_context
[1]
https://github.com/openstack/rally/blob/master/rally/common/broker.py#L39-L40

Change-Id: Ieab25e531382e5c7832eeaecb962d6139a654b96
Closes-bug: #1417281

[{'created': '2015-10-15 14:13:15.000000000', 'message': "Remove oslo.policy implementation tests from keystone

oslo.policy 0.12.0 contains a change to use requests to do the http
check rather than urllib. This change caused keystone tests to fail
because the keystone tests were mocking urllib, making assumptions
about how oslo.policy is implemented. Keystone doesn't need to test
internal features of oslo.policy, so these tests are removed.

Change-Id: I9d6e4950b9fe75cbb94100c8effdcec002642027
Closes-Bug: 1505374
(cherry picked from commit 6016d017004acaae288312b196ef07ea98e9962d)
"}]
commit_message:
Remove oslo.policy implementation tests from keystone

oslo.policy 0.12.0 contains a change to use requests to do the http
check rather than urllib. This change caused keystone tests to fail
because the keystone tests were mocking urllib, making assumptions
about how oslo.policy is implemented. Keystone doesn't need to test
internal features of oslo.policy, so these tests are removed.

Change-Id: I9d6e4950b9fe75cbb94100c8effdcec002642027
Closes-Bug: 1505374
(cherry picked from commit 6016d017004acaae288312b196ef07ea98e9962d)

commit_message:
Update docs for i18n exception

Adding commonly used exception to import translation functions directly
from i18n modules.

Added example as well to the import template.

Removed the old reference to oslo-incubator which used to host these
functions.

Change-Id: I8f8e56198e6a5072ef6b98e7315276aad83f3ba3

commit_message:
Collect additional MySQL stats using dstat CSV

We need the new 'dstat-plugins' in the venv-requirements to add the
mysql5-innodb plugin. In the future other OpenStack-specific plugins
may land there before they can be shipped upstream.

Change-Id: I7ecf5ef7f515afec4524be50ad940ddd1744cec5
implements: counter-inspection

commit_message:
Add script to get dstat counters

We want to grab just one snapshot of the counters before and after
various events. This is incomplete, and only uses the openstack-rabbitmq
plugin, but other plugins will be added that are deemed significant.
These counters will then be pushed into graphite.openstack.org on each
successful gate test run and will form the basis for analysing what
counters are useful for predicting scale problems.

Change-Id: Ib9f117fc9d3cd6adc69676e2db229e73a771a729
implements: counter-inspection

commit_message:
Add dstat-plugins project

This is a set of plugins for use in OpenStack QA. It is starting life
as a fork of dstat's upstream git repository of plugins because those
are not released in any way, and we need them. We will also be adding
more plugins, and submitting them to dstat for inclusion.

We will be working to try and get dstat to release more often and on
pypi so that we can consume all plugins there, but it will be a long
time until that will be stable and regular enough to depend on for the
purposes of the counter-inspection QA spec.

Change-Id: I57c4821014bde6272310734ac564d6f9b58b9fd7
Depends-On: I3ad971cfa33789ade733e8fb92ff51d487078638
implements: counter-inspection

commit_message:
Add dstat-plugins to QA

These plugins will be used to meter devstack runs in the gate for data
collection purposes and to assist developers working on performance and
scale improvements.

Change-Id: I186d0d74a11cdf162b2dd18e44c631e460360421

commit_message:
Handle new release versions in doc publishing

OpenStack has stopped using date based versioning. Dates sort before
shorter semver'd versions which breaks the doc builds determination if
the docs should be writting to root of doc location or /$TAG. We can use
the old hack that we have in place for the clients on all the projects
now to fix this.

Change-Id: I71b0bb6604a9adf3cb898d0b3fdff77f900f83d4

This Vagrant installation configure and deploy two nodes,
one a controller and one is compute node and deploy them
with Dragonflow as their Neutron plugin.

subject: Remove the try_except_pass plugin
messages:
[{'account_id': 8119, 'date': '2015-10-09 06:26:32.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-09 06:27:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-bandit-python34 http://logs.openstack.org/28/232928/1/check/gate-bandit-python34/e788fd5/ : SUCCESS in 52s
- gate-bandit-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/28/232928/1/check/gate-bandit-pep8/5649562/ : SUCCESS in 37s
- gate-bandit-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/28/232928/1/check/gate-bandit-python27/962cb46/ : SUCCESS in 46s'}, {'account_id': 11861, 'date': '2015-10-09 07:09:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I tend to agree but this was Tim's baby, let's see what he says."}, {'account_id': 11716, 'date': '2015-10-09 11:00:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Well, at the time I considered (and still do) that not warning when an exception is generated is a security issue. If someone is trying to break an application or service, they may try fuzzing it or intelligently sending inputs that are likely to cause errors in an effort to break it or gain intel. This will result in an increase in the number of exceptions being reported and could alert a monitoring service that something is up. If these exceptions are just silently swallowed then no such monitoring is possible..... that being said, if several people feel strongly that Bandit is not the best place for this then I wont stand in the way of its removal.'}, {'account_id': 11716, 'date': '2015-10-09 12:20:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

It may also be worth noting that other static analysers (HP's Fortify for example) warn on this issue."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-13 17:36:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change or one of its cross-repo dependencies was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of its repository. Please rebase the change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 8119, 'date': '2015-10-13 22:18:11.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-13 22:46:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-bandit-python34 http://logs.openstack.org/28/232928/2/check/gate-bandit-python34/8e525bc/ : SUCCESS in 54s
- gate-bandit-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/28/232928/2/check/gate-bandit-pep8/aa483e1/ : SUCCESS in 38s
- gate-bandit-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/28/232928/2/check/gate-bandit-python27/0e05059/ : SUCCESS in 47s'}, {'account_id': 6802, 'date': '2015-10-14 13:50:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 11029, 'date': '2015-10-14 14:46:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Hey Eric, any response to Tim's comment above?  It seems like somewhat of a grey area wrt. being a 'security' issue or not; as long as the test isn't too noisy or expensive to run/maintain, I'd be inclined to keep it - maybe with a tweak to the wording of the issue to add a little more context when it is reported."}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-10-15 14:44:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Yes, having try except there is better than having unhandled exceptions which can leak data to the attacker.

Yes, using pass is not actively harmful.

No, that doesn't mean we should remove this. If you're not logging anything for audits or doing anything else, you're not being defensive. I think this is a valid warning, I'd be willing to lower its severity if it isn't already low, but that's about it."}, {'account_id': 8119, 'date': '2015-10-15 17:43:55.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Ok, I will leave it since some feel its useful.'}]

commit_message:
Remove the try_except_pass plugin

The try_except_pass plugin test is not really a check for a security
issue.  It's more of a hacking check.  I don't think it belongs in
bandit.  Its probably better served as a flake8 plugin.

Change-Id: Ic40031ecd504f0efb5654743bd09ba1caab492a5

- gate-monasca-agent-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/00/235000/1/check/gate-monasca-agent-python27/77f5c5c/ : SUCCESS in 39s'}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2015-10-15 16:35:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2

This change should probably be adandoned as this is not a robust test.'}, {'account_id': 12443, 'date': '2015-10-15 17:43:54.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Floating IPs may be an inconclusive vector for ping checks, as not all VMs would have them, and even if they did, security policies for the VM may disallow ICMP.

A better verification would be to use the private IPs, but detect and route through the tenant's correct namespace, also detecting the security policies for the VM and not bothering with a ping test if the security group does not allow ICMP."}]

Libvirt - Prefer floating IPs for ping test

original method is retained as a fallback.

commit_message:
Fixed Version number on setup.cfg for new Kilo revision

Kilo has a new revision and the number was wrong in our
version of the setup.cfg file.

Also removed the collector from the list of services to run
from the beginning and reduced the log storage to avoid filling
the disk fast.

Change-Id: I6b02b94c7fa36fecab73a3010da30b40faa87ee8

commit_message:
Create a version package

There are files hanging around the top level directory that only
handle the versioning routes of keystone (/v2.0 and /v3).

These should be moved to their own package to further isolate
these APIs.

Closes-Bug: #1504892
DocImpact

Change-Id: Ica0ddcbeb6f7fc00a4ad3919fa16bf135637a607

commit_message:
Fix bay-create failure without "name"

Currently magnum allow to create bay without name. But it's failed
because `cert_manager.generate_certificates_to_bay` requires bay
"name".
This fixes it to use bay "uuid" instead of bay "name".

Change-Id: I5da8910fcf8b71f9521abb48e72dc178c3785104
Closes-Bug: #1506314

commit_message:
Pass wait to add_ips_to_server

If we are creating a server with auto_ip and waiting for it, we
should also wait for the ip, as well as the server.

Monty is working on a patch to obsolete this, but in the interim,
this works.

Change-Id: I26bc94408441edf067493b7ffd50eebd9dd95e75

commit_message:
Add task format converter

Task and SubTask classes are introduced that
incapsulate differences in formats of task
configuration and perform corresponding conversion.

Change-Id: I93ccdcd51296ace64c1fb99059080d47e1853d93

Add check for weak elliptic curve keys

This expanded check looks for EC keys that are less than 160 bits
(high severity) or 224 bits (medium severity).

The description looks correct.

One more point could be added if found appropriate:

Such attacks can still be feasible even if the data is being sent. For example if the user send only a few bytes of data, the image record will still be created an the image would be set to a different status (queued, saving, killed). In all these statuses the user has access rights to the image record vs. deleted status when they are revoked.

I am adding a +1 to indicate that the description is correct, the completeness aspect -- I am not so sure.

Thanks a ton for taking care of this.

A user with N number of image records, where N is a very large number relative to the DB & proxy capacity and speed will still be able to DOS Glance API service by making the GET calls often. It is also worth to note that GET calls are rather not restricted by rate limiting to ensure a good user experience.'}, {'account_id': 2537, 'date': '2015-10-07 01:30:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

For example if the user send only a few bytes of data, the image record will still be created an the image would be set to a different status (queued, saving, killed). In all these statuses the user has access rights to the image record vs. deleted status when they are revoked.


A user with N number of image records, where N is a very large number relative to the DB & proxy capacity and speed will still be able to DOS Glance API service by making the GET calls often. It is also worth to note that GET calls are rather not restricted by rate limiting to ensure a good user experience.

commit_message:
Fix documentation around regions

It turns out region_name is an important parameter - it's not
just another kwarg that will get passed through.

Change-Id: I5cca8d324a1dcd1355991df793fe29eedfa15dc0

commit_message:
Use memcache for consoleauth and horizon

Unfortunately there was no was to avoid memcache for consoleauth, so
we might as well take advantage of it for Horizon as well.

Change-Id: Idd338a025b031f6b50fe0c9f03c2c8d862f9d4c0
Closes-Bug: #1504606
Closes-Bug: #1504800
(cherry picked from commit 2ea87ebdb7b15011c2825d23dc160ef0aa76fa0e)

commit_message:
Avoid name collisions with tripleo-ci jobs

The tripleo-ci jobs were using a regex that just looked for
*-tripleo* in the job name, which also matches tripleo-common and
python-tripleoclient.  This causes the py34 jobs for those projects
to sometimes get scheduled to precise nodes that don't have a py34
interpreter installed.

This changes the tripleo-ci jobs to be named tripleo-ci-* and
updates the regex appropriately so it will no longer match non-toci
jobs.

Change-Id: Ie4d803574221b936b249673436db36fd75940587

commit_message:
/etc/murano/murano.conf created before configuring

Ensure that the common package is installed before attempting any
configuration. Without this you have resource ordering issues.

Change-Id: I30c8a9d1f9458ff653ca0e442bca33ab30bf74f7

commit_message:
Add setup option to skip all service/user config

In addition to configuring monitoring plugins, the monasca-setup code
currently attempts to automatically configure and start users and services,
which may not be desirable if other mechanisms are used for this, so add
"--install_plugins_only" option to disable all changes to user and service
configuration.

Change-Id: I79d2f9dc8ac17895918620e7a062441bdde93477

commit_message:
The "ALLOWED_HOSTS" configure error in local_settings file.

"ALLOWED_HOSTS= '*'" should be "ALLOWED_HOSTS= ['*', ]" in
install-guide.

Closes-bug: #1505086

commit_message:
Made error fields in ng launch instance workflow more visible

During UX review, feedback was given that fields with errors in the new
angular launch instance workflow should have a more obvious line/glow
around them.  Currently, the "has-warning" class is being used for
fields that have errors, which gives the fields a light yellow glow
around them upon invalid input.  This change simply switches the class
applied to these fields to the "has-error" class.  This class gives the
fields a darker red glow that is easier to see and tell that an invalid
input has been entered.

Change-Id: I5a28d4429a723e68d93509a178e32fe5225bc95a
Closes-Bug: #1445729

Reformat job flows

Scenario framework started support of several edp job
flows, so it's better to use explicit jobs in plugins
flows.

commit_message:
Upgraded InfluxDB to 0.9.4.1

InfluxDB 0.9.4.x has huge performance improvements over 0.9.1.

Also there have been some issues with the persister storing data
when the load went above the 750K measurements.

The other significant improvement is that counting measurements
now is fast since Influx keeps a count instead of performing a
full table scan.

Change-Id: Ibe7d35184848a6cd8533e957bb04e71db9413155

commit_message:
Add test coverage for auth_type 'credential'

These changes add test coverage by ensuring username, password, domain,
and region inputs should show when the login auth_type is 'credential'.

Closes-Bug: #1499145

commit_message:
Improve readability of dockerfiles and cleanup

* Added newlines to long RUN commands in dockerfiles.
* Removed storage-* containers (obsolete since 6.0)
* Removed shotgun workaround in mcollective container.
* Change disable of mcollective service in start.sh,
  rather than blocking init script in Dockerfile
* Cleaned up duplicate packages already included in
  fuel/centos base container.
* Moved hiera default yaml workaround to fuel/centos

Change-Id: Ifd8740735c676f6e500795aa05123ede4d72ae92
Closes-Bug: #1482232

commit_message:
Remove hardcoded version from dockerctl config

* Fuel version number fallback should be determined by RPM spec,
  not hardcoded in config
* Fix dockerctl config template to use fact fuel_version
* Add %check section to ensure sed works and strips out
  placeholder version string

Change-Id: I28032852517ec8f7e959ad48a04621ec3e33fea1
Closes-bug: #1501368

Please do not patch bugs prior to triage, especially for the installation guide.'}, {'account_id': 16986, 'date': '2015-09-22 02:25:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Matthew
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/How_To_Contribute#Triaging_bugs
"You can contribute instructions on how to fix a given bug, and set it to Triaged. Or you can directly fix it: assign the bug to yourself, set it to In progress, branch the code, implement the fix, and propose your change for merging into trunk !"

According to the instruction, I think contributor can directly fix it. Is there some underlying rules here？ Or the statement in wiki is out of date.'}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2015-09-22 03:12:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Good catch. We should probably fix the rules for bug triage and patches for the installation guide. In the meantime, the bug associated with this patch essentially says "change X to Y" without any reasoning. We periodically test the installation guide, especially near a release, and address almost all real issues shortly after release. Most bugs these days arise from typos, skipping steps, and various host configuration problems rather than real issues with the guide. Patching the installation guide without evidence of a real issue almost always breaks it in some other, sometimes obscure way. In this case, the patch changes a file that pertains to all OpenStack services and therefore could potentially break all of them.'}, {'account_id': 16986, 'date': '2015-09-22 05:21:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Matthew Thank you for your clarification.'}, {'account_id': 16986, 'date': '2015-10-03 07:30:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I think the script works well with V3 since it specifies "OS_USER_DOMAIN_ID".
One place should be improved is inconsistence.
At the beginning, it use v2 api. But it only mentions v3 here, which may confuse people. People may ask why the script can only use "export OS_AUTH_URL=http://controller:35357/v3"'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-04 16:39:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change or one of its cross-repo dependencies was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of its repository. Please rebase the change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2015-10-15 16:29:53.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Bug not valid.'}]

[{'created': '2015-09-21 14:10:37.000000000', 'message': 'Fix client environment scripts in Install Guide

On editing the admin-openrc.sh file, the following line should read
"v2.0" in the end, instead of "v3":

export OS_AUTH_URL=http://controller:35357/v3

Also, editing the demo-openrc.sh file, the following line should read
"v2.0" in the end, instead of "v3":

export OS_AUTH_URL=http://controller:5000/v3

Change-Id: I6b48a997c8579714e416218df39f35d0aba3dba1
Closes-bug: #1497328
'}]
commit_message:
Fix client environment scripts in Install Guide

On editing the admin-openrc.sh file, the following line should read
"v2.0" in the end, instead of "v3":

export OS_AUTH_URL=http://controller:35357/v3

Also, editing the demo-openrc.sh file, the following line should read
"v2.0" in the end, instead of "v3":

export OS_AUTH_URL=http://controller:5000/v3

Change-Id: I6b48a997c8579714e416218df39f35d0aba3dba1
Closes-bug: #1497328

commit_message:
Replace exc.message with six.text_type(exc)

On Python 3, the message attribute of the Exception class was
removed.

Partially implements: blueprint solum-python3
Change-Id: I6f287c611a97ce44193fad5b9bacdaddefa50073

commit_message:
Fix grenade shutdown script

Due to some fix in devstack, using the old lib/heat library doesn't work
anymore, so let's replicate the stop_heat function.

Change-Id: I8e7c62962cef29e35c37ad98a1646630388fb4ab
Closes-Bug: #1506462

[{'created': '2015-10-15 11:23:21.000000000', 'message': "consistent version format reporting

Currently the glanceclient had a couple of places where it was
returning an 'int' type for the version. This is inconsistent
and leads to problems for consumers that expect a string.

commit_message:
consistent version format reporting

Currently the glanceclient had a couple of places where it was
returning an 'int' type for the version. This is inconsistent
and leads to problems for consumers that expect a string.

This fix makes the version type consistent for both v1 and v2.

commit_message:
Bringing the Sahara Bandit config current

There have been several changes in Bandit since the Sahara profile
was implemented.  This commit brings the Sahara config up to date
by:
  - changing info to severity to low
  - adding a couple of plugin configs - currently unused

It should be noted that upstream Bandit config has recently had
some changes to make it more organized and readable.  It's
probably worth implementing a new profile for Sahara, based on
upstream Bandit's example profile, soon.

Change-Id: I37d62708282a4aa830d84e2a1749ac53d3923a0a

commit_message:
Place restrict options to NTP explicitly

To avoid undesirable restrict options in target
config file, pass them explicitly when ntp task
executed.

Also noop tests for ntp manifests change such way
that they really run now.

Change-Id: I110b4b7c2e42dffc9449f54689236ff1582717cb
Closes-Bug: #1505235

commit_message:
Add option for detailed template error

Add option detailed_template_error for informative
error during template and environment parsing.

yaml.SafeLoader returns error with template snippet where
error has been occurred instead of CSafeLoader. But
CSafeLoader is faster. So, if user wants to get more
informative error, use slower but more detailed SafeLoader
for yaml loading.

Change-Id: Ied0a573a00eb5f564dea0c636da1301de5de9ea7
Closes-bug: #1496361

commit_message:
Detect setting locals with subshell commands

The return status of "local" is always 0, so something like

 local foo=$(failing command)

doesn't trigger a failure under "set -e".  Missing "failing command"'s
failure has been a source of problems within devstack.

This is added as a warning

Change-Id: Ia0957b47187c3dcadd46154b17022c4213781112

commit_message:
Fixing grenade job for upgrades from liberty

* Grenade base/target branches has been changed,
  so now it upgrades from liberty to master.Few
  updates were made to make it work.

* "image show" of openstackclient doesn't
  work with v2 version which is by default. v1
  will be used instead.

Closes-bug: #1503322

Change-Id: I16609310f729d77a6edbbcff4f7ebf0cd4e1a17a

commit_message:
Fix cap on python-glanceclient

stable/juno g-r cap on glanceclient<=0.15.0 conflicts with
glanceclient caps in stable/kilo g-r of >=0.15.0.

We need to adjust the juno cap to <0.15.0 so we can release
0.14.x versions of glanceclient from the stable/juno branch.

This will allow Ie6547d1a5501f2d2ec74d3ec4808c26a48ffc7fb to
get into glanceclient 0.14.3 which can fix the broken horizon
stable/juno Ic7516b79ed1eea1330f008ce83c8727fd974bdd3.

Change-Id: I3f9d3fe4c5688685fb9afe1762b698c4f86a4a68

commit_message:
Block oslo.messaging 2.6.1 release

The oslo.messaging-2.6.1 has broken Ceilometer Jenkins job two days, The
change[1] could hopefully fix the issue, but it is better to block the
oslo.messaging-2.6.1 to make Ceilometer Jenkins alive now.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/234372/

Related-Bug: #1505730
Change-Id: Ibb2a8c18651c601c844c3bc9d89f18ae032accf8
Depends-On: Id1e58a9db0d277de2f30de54db97040811f40ff2

commit_message:
Block oslo.messaging 2.6.1 release

The oslo.messaging-2.6.1 has broken Ceilometer Jenkins job two days, The
change[1] could hopefully fix the issue, but it is better to block the
oslo.messaging-2.6.1 to make Ceilometer Jenkins alive now.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/234372/

Related-Bug: #1505730
Change-Id: Id1e58a9db0d277de2f30de54db97040811f40ff2

Remove Solum since it doesn't follow the cycle

Solum is not a Liberty deliverable, it doesn't follow the
release cycle nor does it have stable branches.

commit_message:
Disallow null values in metrics

"value": null in the josn was being converted to 0
This captures value = null and returns an error

Change-Id: I0b942e5d319505bce266510ac99e952a79c23ee6

This LGTM, thanks Ramesh :)'}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2015-09-21 15:02:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: Code-Review-1

Hi Ramesh. Sorry, maybe I shouldn't -1 but I'd like an answer before it gets merged. I see that the config is mentioned in the spec (which I either didn't read or didn't catch).

For cleaning [0], we document that it is enabled via [conductor] clean_nodes=true, followed by a config per clean step, that can be used to set the priority for that clean step (or disable it via priority=0).

I find it confusing to introduce a temporary [iscsi_deploy] enable_cleaning that is used for what? To prevent accidental start-of-cleaning (?) for DIB ramdisks which don't support cleaning? Why don't we just hard-code that case or is it because we don't know that it is a DIB ramdisk? Maybe I'm missing something.


[0] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/ironic/deploy/cleaning.html"}, {'account_id': 9315, 'date': '2015-09-21 15:07:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

Hi Ruby, yes, this is to prevent Ironic from accidentally trying to boot up ramdisk after tearing down an instance and waiting for it to heartbeat back to start cleaning. 

We just deprecated dib ramdisk in liberty. If we enabled this automatically by default, this would immediately break workflow of people using dib ramdisk in their environments. This would be bad as they would always see nodes ending up in CLEANFAIL in their environment until they switch to agent ramdisk. In a way, we will be forcing them to switch to agent ramdisk without giving them time, which would be bad.'}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2015-09-21 15:29:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

I still don't understand. What does 'enabled this automatically' mean? Isn't the [conductor] clean_nodes config used for enabling cleaning? Followed by the config for a clean step?

If it is a DIB ramdisk, would someone set [conductor] clean_nodes=True?"}, {'account_id': 10343, 'date': '2015-09-21 21:00:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: Code-Review-2

We've decided to punt this to the Mitaka cycle so we can take some time and figure out what the right thing to do with this config is."}, {'account_id': 10343, 'date': '2015-09-25 13:47:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: -Code-Review

This commit adds the following methods to ISCSIDeploy
to enable in-band cleaning.

- get_clean_steps
- execute_clean_step
- prepare_cleaning
- tear_down_cleaning

It also adds the following code to prevent nodes to be
stuck at CLEANWAIT forever if bash ramdisk is used:

- Send the bash ramdisk parameters (deploy_key,
  iscsi_target_iqn, etc) while booting the deploy ramdisk
  for cleaning. It will enable bash ramdisk to invoke
  pass_deploy_info vendor passthru.
- If node is in CLEANWAIT in pass_deploy_info vendor passthru,
  then we set the clean steps for the node and ask conductor
  to resume cleaning.
- We also skip validation for pass_deploy_info vendor passthru
  if node is in CLEANWAIT state.
- ISCSIDeploy.get_clean_steps will return an empty list if
  bash ramdisk is used. It is detected by presence of
  agent_url in node's driver_internal_info.

Change-Id: Ie89ffc0bf649742a95cc02b4a54e956ae6682503
Implements: blueprint iscsi-deploy-in-band-cleaning
"}]
commit_message:
Add support for in-band cleaning in ISCSIDeploy

This commit adds the following methods to ISCSIDeploy
to enable in-band cleaning.

- get_clean_steps
- execute_clean_step
- prepare_cleaning
- tear_down_cleaning

It also adds the following code to prevent nodes to be
stuck at CLEANWAIT forever if bash ramdisk is used:

- Send the bash ramdisk parameters (deploy_key,
  iscsi_target_iqn, etc) while booting the deploy ramdisk
  for cleaning. It will enable bash ramdisk to invoke
  pass_deploy_info vendor passthru.
- If node is in CLEANWAIT in pass_deploy_info vendor passthru,
  then we set the clean steps for the node and ask conductor
  to resume cleaning.
- We also skip validation for pass_deploy_info vendor passthru
  if node is in CLEANWAIT state.
- ISCSIDeploy.get_clean_steps will return an empty list if
  bash ramdisk is used. It is detected by presence of
  agent_url in node's driver_internal_info.

Change-Id: Ie89ffc0bf649742a95cc02b4a54e956ae6682503
Implements: blueprint iscsi-deploy-in-band-cleaning

    This report is produced quarterly to give Community Managers and
    OpenStack Foundation's management better insights on development
    activities and online conversations. The quantitative and qualitative
    assessment start from tracking actions across all OpenStack git
    repositories, gerrit code reviews, bug trackers as well as IRC
    channels, mailing lists and questions/answers.

commit_message:
Use memcache for consoleauth and horizon

Unfortunately there was no was to avoid memcache for consoleauth, so
we might as well take advantage of it for Horizon as well.

Change-Id: Idd338a025b031f6b50fe0c9f03c2c8d862f9d4c0
Closes-Bug: #1504606

This will not be a one-time occurrence.

Now consider how we build images. While this upper-constraint might be good if you want to _build_ liberty say 2 years down the road, likely the distro packaging won't work. If you build liberty today that docker images is golden forever.

commit_message:
Use openstack/requirements for repeatable builds

Add this repo to the openstack-base image, and use the upper-constraints
to install the client packages. Will follow up with dependant patches
for the child images to reduce the risk of breaking everything at once.

--

Background:

Many dependencies in the requirements.txt of OpenStack components have
quite loose version requirements, in many cases they will just specify a
minimum version (e.g. WebOb>=1.2.3).

The result of this is that given a Kolla image for Keystone built today,
another build of the exact same ref of Keystone could be broken
tomorrow, due to it picking up a later unsupported dependency.

The https://github.com/openstack/requirements repo exists to bring some
sanity to this situation. (It also outlines other problems it solves in
it's readme).

We also may like to checkout the stable/liberty branch of this project
in our liberty branch, once it appears.

Change-Id: Iccb4e99f8e4b6659a19c1817d0f4c697824af25c
Partial-Bug: #1505306

Roland,

Thanks for the review.  Yes, the following works for existing clusters:

[DEV] root@dev02-monascadb-001:~# vsql -c 'alter table monmetrics.measurements alter column value_meta set data type varchar(8192);'
ALTER TABLE

Brad"}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2015-10-13 19:58:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Cool, we might need to use that one ourselves.

I'll +1, but Deklan will need to look at this."}, {'account_id': 12512, 'date': '2015-10-13 20:37:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi Brad-

Several questions.

What encoding are you/we currently using? Is it utf8?

If utf8, then the number of bytes used for each character will vary. 

Does Vertica use "8192" to specify bytes or characters? If characters then we should not have to consider the encoding.

Why 8192? What is special about that number?

Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 11155, 'date': '2015-10-14 15:28:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 8126, 'date': '2015-10-14 15:29:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Deklan,

We'll limit the number of characters to 2048, and assume the worst case for encoding (X4).  It seems VJDBC is UTF-16, but Roland found some links that hint that it could end up being UTF-32, so we're just being safe here.

Thanks!
Brad"}, {'account_id': 12512, 'date': '2015-10-14 15:34:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

It looks like at this point, we are not really sure what the actually encoding in the vertica db is?'}, {'account_id': 8126, 'date': '2015-10-14 15:45:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Per our conversation in weekly meeting, UTF-16, which could be 1 to 4 octets per char...'}, {'account_id': 6650, 'date': '2015-10-14 21:29:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 12512, 'date': '2015-10-15 14:29:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 8126, 'date': '2015-10-15 14:43:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-15 14:43:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

commit_message:
Ceph: fix PG count number

Fix PG groups overestimation. Pre 7.0 FUEL use
equal pg_count for all pools, which leads to large
PG per OSD. This change would split pools on two
groups - small and large. All pools would get
at least small fixed amount of PG max(64, OSD_NUM/pool_sz).
Large pools would share the rest PG groups
accordingly to their weight. Only really used pools
get PG.

Closes-Bug: #1464656
Partial-blueprint: ceph-pool-pg-num
Change-Id: I79d917d01fb5593f132643d99cdeb9218b1ec625

commit_message:
Add transitive reduction filter for task graphs

  Remove 'pydot_ng' that doesn't support transitive reduction filtering.
  Add '--tred' option for CLI.
  Usage example:

      fuel graph --render graph.gv --tred
      fuel graph --render graph.gv --dir ./output/dir/ --tred

Change-Id: Ibfd7112dc0751df9bcadd0ab46e29f5159cbb3a5
Closes-bug: #1443446

commit_message:
Avoid starting rabbitmq server as root

Starting rabbitmq-server causes rabbitmq (and dependent
processes) to start as root user, causing undesirable
results. epmd process stays running as root until killed
by OCF scripts. It is more desirable to start rabbitmq
manually when Puppet tells it to.

Additionally, rabbitmq-plugins must be run as root
(in order to set /etc/rabbitmq/enabled_plugins), but as
a consequence, it starts epmd and leaves it running.
This can be worked around by starting epmd as rabbitmq
user before evaluating any plugins.

Added test for ensuring all RabbitMQ related processes
are running as rabbitmq user.

Upstream proposed change:
https://github.com/puppetlabs/puppetlabs-rabbitmq/pull/403

Change-Id: Ia6e5392c9d16d1be0ea166a61402d2103c5d4453
Closes-Bug: #1483249

commit_message:
Added support for new block device format in vmops

Modified vmops methods to make use of the new block device format.

This new format allows for more flexibility when using block device,
such as the ability to select the bus for the attachment and the boot
index.

Partially implements: blueprint hyper-v-block-device-mapping-support

This patch includes the following updates based on the updated source in

"}, {'created': '2015-10-12 12:26:27.000000000', 'message': "Update Nova Configuration for Liberty

This patch includes the following updates based on the updated
source in Nova's Liberty release:
 - api-paste.ini
 - policy.json
 - rootwrap.d/compute.filters
 - rootwrap.d/network.filters

The Nova S3 and v3 API's have been removed in Liberty, so all
related variables and configuration file entries have been
removed.

The Nova EC2 API is deprecated in Liberty. All related variables in
OpenStack-Ansible and configuration files have been removed as all
deployers are recommended to make use of the actively developed
replacement: https://github.com/stackforge/ec2-api

The Nova v2 and v1.1 API's are enabled using the upstream default
compatibility layer. Neither of these versions will be registered in
the service catalog.

The default API version is set to v2.1. For new environments, no
other API versions are registered in the service catalog.

DocImpact
UpgradeImpact
Implements: blueprint liberty-release
Change-Id: Ie5a42059c10e7fd0bfc4dba8d87dea3f32db968e

replacement: https://github.com/stackforge/ec2-api

commit_message:
Update Nova Configuration for Liberty

This patch includes the following updates based on the updated
source in Nova's Liberty release:
 - api-paste.ini
 - policy.json
 - rootwrap.d/compute.filters
 - rootwrap.d/network.filters

The Nova S3 and v3 API's have been removed in Liberty, so all
related variables and configuration file entries have been
removed.

The Nova EC2 API is deprecated in Liberty. All related variables in
OpenStack-Ansible and configuration files have been removed as all
deployers are recommended to make use of the actively developed
replacement: https://github.com/stackforge/ec2-api

The Nova v2 and v1.1 API's are enabled using the upstream default
compatibility layer. Neither of these versions will be registered in
the service catalog.

The default API version is set to v2.1. For new environments, no
other API versions are registered in the service catalog.

The following variables have been removed:
 - S3 API
   - nova_s3_service_name
   - nova_s3_service_type
   - nova_s3_service_proto

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-09 02:46:03.000000000', 'message': 'Fix disconnecting necessary iSCSI sessions issue

With "iscsi_use_multipath=true", detaching a multipath iSCSI
volume kills all iSCSI volumes visible from the attached node.
When we use different targets(IQNs) associated with same portal
for each different multipath device, all of the targets will
be deleted via disconnect_volume().

This patch fixes the behavior of detaching volume:

  1. Extract the targets for the detached multipath device.
  2. Delete/disconnect the targets for the detached multipath
     device.

(Ported from I38eafdaee03d136282cfde1fd013e322a4256cc4)

Co-Authored-By: Hiroyuki Eguchi <h-eguchi@az.jp.nec.com>
Closes-Bug: #1382440
Change-Id: I5fdbb5765642bac7263ff616ae4b006d9504547a
(cherry picked from 531398504fcdcffb37e73a254f5a3da1854ef41e)

commit_message:
Fix disconnecting necessary iSCSI sessions issue

With "iscsi_use_multipath=true", detaching a multipath iSCSI
volume kills all iSCSI volumes visible from the attached node.
When we use different targets(IQNs) associated with same portal
for each different multipath device, all of the targets will
be deleted via disconnect_volume().

This patch fixes the behavior of detaching volume:

  1. Extract the targets for the detached multipath device.
  2. Delete/disconnect the targets for the detached multipath
     device.

(Ported from I38eafdaee03d136282cfde1fd013e322a4256cc4)

Co-Authored-By: Hiroyuki Eguchi <h-eguchi@az.jp.nec.com>
Closes-Bug: #1382440
Change-Id: I5fdbb5765642bac7263ff616ae4b006d9504547a
(cherry picked from 531398504fcdcffb37e73a254f5a3da1854ef41e)

Is there any background for this patch?'}, {'account_id': 13720, 'date': '2015-08-27 11:50:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Ethan, the original motivation for this patch was to fix a bug with the encryption script. If you create a stack with a template such as the one given below, the encryption script will fail as the default parameter is an integer which causes an exception in olso.utils.encodeutils.safe_encode function, which is called by the encrypt function. But then I realized that a) storing default parameters as environment parameters is a logical fallacy in itself and b) default parameters are still available in the raw template and are hence still visible to a potential attacker ("makes you think you're safe when you're not"). This patch solves both a) and b) and, as per my testing, solves my original problem since the encryption script does not fail anymore even when a raw_template entry for this template exists in the db.

The template:
heat_template_version: 2014-10-16
parameters:
  flavor:
    type: string
    description: Flavor for the server to be created
    default: 4353
    hidden: true
resources:
  test_server:
    type: "OS::Nova::Server"
    properties:
      name: test-server
      flavor: 2 GB General Purpose v1
      image: Debian 7 (Wheezy) (PVHVM)'}, {'account_id': 13720, 'date': '2015-08-27 11:56:51.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 13720, 'date': '2015-08-27 12:01:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

commit_message:
Don't encrypt default parameters in heat-manage encrypt script

If a parameter has a default value, that must mean that its
not sensitive enough to be hidden. So don't hide it by encryption.

Change-Id: I7257cfce13d8153c5a487d048e0b62abcaefc116
Closes-Bug: #1489157
Closes-Bug: #1488679

element separated by SP characters'

This patch coerces filling associated textual phrase.

commit_message:
Fix Status-Line in HTTP response

There is a strict rule about constructing status line for HTTP:
'...Status-Line, consisting of the protocol version followed by a
numeric status code and its associated textual phrase, with each
element separated by SP characters'
(http://www.faqs.org/rfcs/rfc2616.html)

This patch ensures an associated textual phrase for a status code
is always written in the HTTP response.

Closes-Bug: #1496055
Change-Id: I68d4c41d0c04871eb032d23d7b16aa2bf2c0bb73

commit_message:
Port SolidFire to Python3

Just update solidfire.py and test_solidfire.py
to be python3 compatible.

This also adds test_solidfire to the py34 test
whitelist.

Change-Id: I2a904068beaab8027dec81d8e18f0ce550ceee55
Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-python3

commit_message:
do not create tempest.conf from .sample file

tempest.conf.sample does not exist anymore* so we need to stop relying
on this file to create the tempest.conf configuration file.

* https://github.com/openstack/tempest/commit/c8a39b488b97dd876af39567f8096f15dd36b802

This patch drops the File resource that managed tempest.conf.

Closes-Bug: #1482949
Change-Id: I7c3d20a61aa88a25f1215cccb4cb36168eab05c5
(cherry picked from commit 0e9c5dbf51c0de0514ecef90f065b5c52fb3cfd7)

commit_message:
Reset yum/dnf cache to correct location

Make sure we reset the yum/dnf cache to /var/cache/${YUM}, not just
/var/cache/yum

This was resulting in the F22 fedora-minimal image being larger than
the base-image.  Because F22 fedora-minimal does some installs with
dnf when bootstrapping the chroot before we set "cachedir=" to the
bind-mounted external cache, we have "/var/cache/dnf" created and and
populated with the package meta-data, etc.

When we globally point dnf to /var/cache/yum here, we effectively
orphan the /var/cache/dnf created in those first steps.  dnf doesn't
care, but we end up with two copies of all the package metadata, etc
in "/var/cache/dnf" & "/var/cache/yum".

This also cleans up the sed a bit, by just replacing the lines.

Change-Id: Icc98fe30c34cb941aed4b987647ab67ac34af15a

[{'created': '2015-10-09 02:46:03.000000000', 'message': "optimize multipath call to identify IQN

When detaching a multipath volume in an environment where there
are many attached volumes, excessive multipath calls are
generated and it takes too much time. This issue is due to the
fact that a multipath -ll call against many multipath devices
takes a few seconds.

When detaching a volume, _disconnect_volume_multipath_iscsi()
calls 'multipath -ll <each iscsi device>' against every iscsi
devices. This behavior is to identify the IQNs used by multipath
device, however the IQNs are extracted from one 'multipath -ll'
call without massive 'multipath -ll <each iscsi device>' calls.

This patch changes the behavior of identifying IQNs used by
multipath device:
 1. add an utility to identify IQNs by using multipath device map
    (/dev/sdX => /dev/mapper/XXX) generated by 'multipath -ll'.
 2. replace the current nested for loop to identify the IQNs with
    the utility.

(Ported from I77e6eda950726d7ee9a0d92882d4501e70a0d8f8)

Closes-Bug: #1456480

commit_message:
optimize multipath call to identify IQN

When detaching a multipath volume in an environment where there
are many attached volumes, excessive multipath calls are
generated and it takes too much time. This issue is due to the
fact that a multipath -ll call against many multipath devices
takes a few seconds.

When detaching a volume, _disconnect_volume_multipath_iscsi()
calls 'multipath -ll <each iscsi device>' against every iscsi
devices. This behavior is to identify the IQNs used by multipath
device, however the IQNs are extracted from one 'multipath -ll'
call without massive 'multipath -ll <each iscsi device>' calls.

This patch changes the behavior of identifying IQNs used by
multipath device:
 1. add an utility to identify IQNs by using multipath device map
    (/dev/sdX => /dev/mapper/XXX) generated by 'multipath -ll'.
 2. replace the current nested for loop to identify the IQNs with
    the utility.

(Ported from I77e6eda950726d7ee9a0d92882d4501e70a0d8f8)

Change-Id: I1e5e9eba58a349509e80654ab3058c4ff5d00c0d
Co-Authored-By: Keiichi KII <k-keiichi@bx.jp.nec.com>
Closes-Bug: #1456480
(cherry picked from 06b5167f4f3ecc6c80abc3f3c1c5e16b493ed196)

V-38546: Disable IPv6 system-wide

This is a serious change to consider and it requires a deployer to opt-in.

Implements: blueprint security-hardening

commit_message:
Fixed retrieval of freezer url from keystone catalog

fixed an incorrect placement for when to look for the fallback url
which caused to look for FREEZER_API_URL even if it is present on the
catalog.

Change-Id: I171e80198e6cb91d056a7d3261a34a0f96b10eb4

commit_message:
Raise RuntimeError if db_get_val fails where applicable

It's a bit more graceful to raise RuntimeError than AttributeError, even
though there is no significant difference for users (the port handling
still fails).

This patch touches all places where we call to db_get_val inside the
agent.

The patch will make the agent fail immediately on bridge setup if ovsdb
operations fail, instead of silently proceeding.

Closes-Bug: #1503750
Change-Id: I62a7492dc02c1d06e884fc6179179c8d7b13b440

commit_message:
ISCSI be careful parsing iscsiadm output

Sometimes iscsiadm can output debugging text.
This patch does the same thing that the old
nova libvirt volume code does in being safe
with reading the command line output.  We want
to ensure that we are reading the iqns and ips.

Change-Id: I092a56e52bcea6adb6cb018cd059e6126a1dc07d
Closes-Bug: #1453992
(cherry-picked from 8e6e07e15e083ace62e38f426045d277c6628961)

commit_message:
Implement ceilometer venv support

This commit conditionally allows the os_ceilometer role to
install build and deploy within a venv. This is the new
default behavior of the role however the functionality
can be disabled.

Change-Id: Ic12d0cb2151124fc5150170205d5d226dab53e5b
Implements: blueprint enable-venv-support-within-the-roles
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Add unit test for create_server,list_addresses.

We have a plan to migrate service clients to tempest-lib from Tempest.
However, we are not doing enough tests for service clients now.
This patch adds unit test for create_server, list_addresses, list_address_by_network,
remove bytes_body parameter in delete_server

Change-Id: I5c2f73b87b033baa362360b6add6eabd02f54c38

commit_message:
Add container and disk format parameters

Add the following parameters about glance images.
They are utilized in
tempest.api.image.v2.test_images.BasicOperationsImagesTest and
tempest.api.image.v2.test_images.ListImagesTest.

container_formats:
A list of image's container formats that users can specify.

disk_formats:
A list of image's disk formats that users can specify.

DocImpact
Change-Id: I8153cc8a75d52de8f39260675739174a2ea3b4e4
Partial-Bug: #1483177

commit_message:
Don't mix declaration and set of locals

Ia0957b47187c3dcadd46154b17022c4213781112 proposes to have bashate
find instances of setting a local value.  The issue is that "local"
always returns 0, thus hiding any failure in the commands running to
set the variable.

This is an automated replacement of such instances

Depends-On: I676c805e8f0401f75cc5367eee83b3d880cdef81
Change-Id: I9c8912a8fd596535589b207d7fc553b9d951d3fe

commit_message:
Mаke possible to upgrade Fuel 7.0 to Fuel 8.0

Since we're supporting only one consequent upgrade chain, and current
master is 8.0, let's set 7.0 as previous release and unblock 7.0 -> 8.0
upgrade chain.

Change-Id: I0777ac908af45268760315329d26f4c5ce8c223a
Closes-Bug: #1506380

commit_message:
[Sahara] Add support for proxy node

The Proxy Node feature allows to use one Floating IP for a Sahara
Cluster. This allows to provision large clusters where the number of
Floating IPs is limited.

Boolean enable_proxy paremeter is availble for both Sahara Cluster benchmark
and Sahara Cluster Context. The default value is False.

The feature is supported by Sahara kilo release or newer.

Change-Id: I479893290de140737a5e0ec5dbc19ea211f21c00

commit_message:
Fix attempt to access not existed network group id key in input data

Code of NetworkGroupValidator.validate_network_group utilize 'id' key
(id of the network group being operated on) so its absence will
lead to KeyError exception when the data is not present in payload of the
request, e.g. when user updates certain attributes of the network group
using fuel-client. This patch fixes described problem.

Change-Id: Ida494738ce5d61a6eec20bfa815923c9da6a7d56
Closes-Bug: #1500308

commit_message:
Improve network group validation

The validation for creating network groups and updating
them has been split into two independent methods.
This change also prevents a network group's nodegroup from
being changed.

Change-Id: I0fb6e9c5f77effa8f1c81014f6151dafd98357d8
Closes-bug: #1494842
Closes-bug: #1494974

commit_message:
Swift JSON files looking for rings in the wrong place

For Swift, the *.json.j2 templates are looking under
{{ container_config_directory }} whereas they need to be looking in the
common location for swift which is /var/lib/kolla/swift

Change-Id: I6f0dcbc9a705b36d1d98275ba9ebc56404fe882d
backport: liberty
Closes-Bug: #1504210
(cherry picked from commit 71fbf63c88f2ce08fd640002e04f333d5345c202)

commit_message:
Add small reminder to use latest vagrant

Vagrant is fast moving tech and we've seen some bugs around users using
old distro packaged versions
(https://bugs.launchpad.net/kolla/+bug/1505045).

Change-Id: I37ae4452fd95e8b58aec228d89bd98214ac012df
backport: liberty
(cherry picked from commit b0e997abd9e455d7bf322170e67902c69d80171f)

commit_message:
Also copy over Swift builder files for rings

These are required for certain commands such as inspecting the state of
the rings on a node.

Change-Id: Iaefb252503320d5b4fcefe12f5d43f0aaf25cad6
backport: liberty
Closes-Bug: #1491779
(cherry picked from commit b4fc9cff073991e731c3b37b14318602f0960289)

commit_message:
Make Ceph work for RPM based distributions

Ceph packages need to be installed in nova, glance, and cinder.
Once that is done, Ceph works like a champ!

Change-Id: I296da1d04d0c1bcb729f22e65e432d53d561b49c
backport: liberty
Closes-Bug: #1505549
(cherry picked from commit 1353538644253081f62a6a74e299d102aa9965dd)

commit_message:
Pin Docker version to 1.8.2

Currently Ansible have issues with Docker 1.8.3. We have to pin
version to 1.8.2 before including fix [1] in tagged Ansible
version.

[1] https://github.com/ansible/ansible-modules-core/pull/2258

Change-Id: If802ff118782ec521acfff00e286cde703bf37b3

commit_message:
Implement heat venv support

This commit conditionally allows the os_heat role to
install build and deploy within a venv. This is the new
default behavior of the role however the functionality
can be disabled.

Change-Id: I55c0ad20d67c9d97df9d11d01e4c63fa0a904188
Implements: blueprint enable-venv-support-within-the-roles
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Allow to specify number of retries for puppet task

Now it's possible to specify a number of retries for
puppet task in granural deployment by specifying a new
parameter "retries":

  parameters:
    ...
    retries: 10

By default, there are 2 retries.

Change-Id: I819a019cf488fc1bd0d52b35d1693fcc088125cb
Partial-Bug: #1457794

commit_message:
Add validation for 'retries' param in puppet task

Puppet tasks allow to specify 'retries' param to control
how many retries will be performed in case of problems with
puppet run. It should be validated to only allow integers.
Additionally added example of usage.

DocImpact
Change-Id: I60d192582eacb6561650c1a309d480128b172f7a
Closes-Bug: #1457794
Depends-On: I819a019cf488fc1bd0d52b35d1693fcc088125cb

commit_message:
Just use 'exception_to_unicode' to handle exception to string

This functions primary purposes is to try to safely convert
an exception object into a unicode string, and handle the errors
that may occur due to that, so we can just use that instead.

Change-Id: I0f7fa0b98512fe22325281adf4bd0e1fe6087e98

commit_message:
Remove the iSCSI rescan during disconnect

Doing an iSCSI rescan at disconnect time is pretty
dangerous to do.  iSCSI rescan doesn't make volumes
go away, it makes them show back up.  So during Nova
live migration it will make local scsi volumes show
back up.

Nova live migration first loops over volumes and calls
disconnect_volume, then after that it loops over the volumes
again and call's cinder to terminate_connection.

If disconnect_volume does a rescan, then volumes there were
removed during previous calls will show back up, because cinder's
driver hasn't had a chance to terminate the connection yet
from the array.

Closes-Bug: #1483326
Change-Id: I8708db16a4b9057b09abad9f956fa5a3bb4ba54c
(cherry picked from c0839fa55067e96bf577d16b7b9d825ae7b52aba)

commit_message:
Detect blank variable in trueorfalse

As a follow-on to I8cefb58f49dcd2cb2def8a5071d0892af520e7f7, put in
some detection around missing variable-to-test arguments in
trueorfalse.

Correct a couple of places where we were passing in blank strings,
resulting in the default always being applied.

Add test-cases and enhance the documentation a little.

Depends-On: I8cefb58f49dcd2cb2def8a5071d0892af520e7f7
Change-Id: Icc0eb3808a2b6583828d8c47f0af4181e7e2c75a

commit_message:
Fix the length of auto-generated commit

Currently, the first line of the commit message generated
by migrate_from_tempest.sh is more than 72 characters, which
is the limiting value. This patch enforces that git-message-rule.

Change-Id: I6108c9a1602b8daa04a94f97d219ff4fb4a43371

commit_message:
Merge tag '1.0.0'

This is a null-merge of the 1.0.0 release tag back into the master
branch so that the 1.0.0 tag will appear in the git commit history of
the master branch. It contains no actual changes to the master branch,
regardless of how our code review system's UI represents it. Please
ask in #openstack-infra if you have any questions, and otherwise try
to merge this as quickly as possible to avoid later conflicts on the
master branch.

Change-Id: I3838051eb86d13bf61d5f007fe7913452b757835

commit_message:
Use a stopwatch in 'forever_retry_uncaught_exceptions'

We might as well use a oslo.utils stopwatch object to
track the periodic 60 seconds logging on exceptions instead
of manually using time.time.

Change-Id: If47a6e91c92942297d923c54b02d285d075fdc70

commit_message:
Log output from ping command

Today we don't log this information which could be useful to see that
this is actually occurring successfully or failure.

 To avoid the ping verbose output, logging is put around the call to
call_until_true. A log message before indicates the attemption of caller
and one after indicates the ping result whether it's as expected.

Change-Id: Ib39ce3d4c9077d04e13cd86973fcb95d878ead3c
Closes-bug: #1373055
